# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quantum-mechanics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In quantum mechanics, the **Pauli exclusion principle** states that two or more identical particles with half-integer spins (i.e., fermions) cannot simultaneously occupy the same quantum state within a system that obeys the laws of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This principle was formulated by Austrian physicist Wolfgang Pauli in 1925 for electrons, and later extended to all fermions with his spin–statistics theorem of 1940.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] For example, if two electrons reside in the same orbital, then their values of *n*, *ℓ*, and *mℓ* are equal.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In that case, the two values of *m*s (spin) pair must be different.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Since the only two possible values for the spin projection *m*s are +1/2 and −1/2, it follows that one electron must have *m*s = +1/2 and one *m*s = −1/2.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Particles with an integer spin (bosons) are not subject to the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Any number of identical bosons can occupy the same quantum state, such as photons produced by a laser, or atoms found in a Bose–Einstein condensate.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] A rigorous statement which justifies the exclusion principle is: under the exchange of two identical particles, the total (many-particle) wave function is antisymmetric for fermions and symmetric for bosons.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This means that if the space *and* spin coordinates of two identical particles are interchanged, then the total wave function changes sign (from positive to negative or vice versa) for fermions, but does not change sign for bosons.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] So, if hypothetically two fermions were in the same state—for example, in the same atom in the same orbital with the same spin—then interchanging them would change nothing and the total wave function would be unchanged.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] However, the only way a total wave function can both change sign (which is required for fermions), and also remain unchanged, is that such a function must be zero everywhere, which means such a state cannot exist.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This reasoning does not apply to bosons because the sign does not change.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The Pauli exclusion principle describes the behavior of all fermions (particles with half-integer spin), while bosons (particles with integer spin) are subject to other principles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Fermions include elementary particles such as quarks, electrons and neutrinos.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Additionally, baryons such as protons and neutrons (subatomic particles composed from three quarks) and some atoms (such as helium-3) are fermions, and are therefore described by the Pauli exclusion principle as well.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Atoms can have different overall spin, which determines whether they are fermions or bosons: for example, helium-3 has spin 1/2 and is therefore a fermion, whereas helium-4 has spin 0 and is a boson.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The Pauli exclusion principle underpins many properties of everyday matter, from its large-scale stability to the chemical behavior of atoms.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Half-integer spin means that the intrinsic angular momentum value of fermions is $\hbar =h/2\pi$ (reduced Planck constant) times a half-integer (1/2, 3/2, 5/2, etc.).
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In the theory of quantum mechanics, fermions are described by antisymmetric states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In contrast, particles with integer spin (bosons) have symmetric wave functions and may share the same quantum states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Bosons include the photon, the Cooper pairs which are responsible for superconductivity, and the W and Z bosons.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Fermions take their name from the Fermi–Dirac statistical distribution, which they obey, and bosons take theirs from the Bose–Einstein distribution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In the early 20th century it became evident that atoms and molecules with even numbers of electrons are more chemically stable than those with odd numbers of electrons.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In the 1916 article "The Atom and the Molecule" by Gilbert N.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Lewis, for example, the third of his six postulates of chemical behavior states that the atom tends to hold an even number of electrons in any given shell, and especially to hold eight electrons, which he assumed to be typically arranged symmetrically at the eight corners of a cube.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In 1919 chemist Irving Langmuir suggested that the periodic table could be explained if the electrons in an atom were connected or clustered in some manner.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Groups of electrons were thought to occupy a set of electron shells around the nucleus.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In 1922, Niels Bohr updated his model of the atom by assuming that certain numbers of electrons (for example 2, 8 and 18) corresponded to stable "closed shells".
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Pauli looked for an explanation for these numbers, which were at first only empirical.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] At the same time he was trying to explain experimental results of the Zeeman effect in atomic spectroscopy and in ferromagnetism.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] He found an essential clue in a 1924 paper by Edmund C.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This led Pauli to realize that the complicated numbers of electrons in closed shells can be reduced to the simple rule of *one* electron per state if the electron states are defined using four quantum numbers.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] For this purpose he introduced a new two-valued quantum number, identified by Samuel Goudsmit and George Uhlenbeck as electron spin.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The Pauli exclusion principle with a single-valued many-particle wavefunction is equivalent to requiring the wavefunction to be antisymmetric with respect to exchange.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] If $|x\rangle$ and $|y\rangle$ range over the basis vectors of the Hilbert space describing a one-particle system, then the tensor product produces the basis vectors $|x,y\rangle =|x\rangle \otimes |y\rangle$ of the Hilbert space describing a system of two such particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] where each *A*(*x*, *y*) is a (complex) scalar coefficient.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This implies *A*(*x*, *y*) = 0 when *x* = *y*, which is Pauli exclusion.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] It is true in any basis since local changes of basis keep antisymmetric matrices antisymmetric.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This is zero, because the two particles have zero probability to both be in the superposition state $|x\rangle +|y\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The first and last terms are diagonal elements and are zero, and the whole sum is equal to zero.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] For a system with *n* > 2 particles, the multi-particle basis states become *n*-fold tensor products of one-particle basis states, and the coefficients of the wavefunction $A(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n})$ are identified by *n* one-particle states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The condition of antisymmetry states that the coefficients must flip sign whenever any two states are exchanged: $A(\ldots ,x_{i},\ldots ,x_{j},\ldots )=-A(\ldots ,x_{j},\ldots ,x_{i},\ldots )$ for any $i\neq j$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The exclusion principle is the consequence that, if $x_{i}=x_{j}$ for any $i\neq j,$ then $A(\ldots ,x_{i},\ldots ,x_{j},\ldots )=0.$ This shows that none of the *n* particles may be in the same state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] According to the spin–statistics theorem, particles with integer spin occupy symmetric quantum states, and particles with half-integer spin occupy antisymmetric states; furthermore, only integer or half-integer values of spin are allowed by the principles of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In relativistic quantum field theory, the Pauli principle follows from applying a rotation operator in imaginary time to particles of half-integer spin.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In one dimension, bosons, as well as fermions, can obey the exclusion principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] A one-dimensional Bose gas with delta-function repulsive interactions of infinite strength is equivalent to a gas of free fermions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The reason for this is that, in one dimension, the exchange of particles requires that they pass through each other; for infinitely strong repulsion this cannot happen.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This model is described by a quantum nonlinear Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In momentum space, the exclusion principle is valid also for finite repulsion in a Bose gas with delta-function interactions, as well as for interacting spins and Hubbard model in one dimension, and for other models solvable by Bethe ansatz.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The ground state in models solvable by Bethe ansatz is a Fermi sphere.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The Pauli exclusion principle helps explain a wide variety of physical phenomena.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] One particularly important consequence of the principle is the elaborate electron shell structure of atoms and the way atoms share electrons, explaining the variety of chemical elements and their chemical combinations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] An electrically neutral atom contains bound electrons equal in number to the protons in the nucleus.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Electrons, being fermions, cannot occupy the same quantum state as other electrons, so electrons have to "stack" within an atom, i.e. have different spins while at the same electron orbital as described below.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] However, the spin can take only two different values (eigenvalues).
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In a lithium atom (Li), with three bound electrons, the third electron cannot reside in a 1s state and must occupy a higher-energy state instead.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The lowest available state is 2s, so that the ground state of Li is 1s22s.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Similarly, successively larger elements must have shells of successively higher energy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The chemical properties of an element largely depend on the number of electrons in the outermost shell; atoms with different numbers of occupied electron shells but the same number of electrons in the outermost shell have similar properties, which gives rise to the periodic table of the elements.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] To test the Pauli exclusion principle for the helium atom, Gordon Drake of the University of Windsor carried out very precise calculations for hypothetical states of the He atom that violate it, which are called **paronic states**.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Deilamian et al. used an atomic beam spectrometer to search for the paronic state 1s2s 1S0 calculated by Drake.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The search was unsuccessful and showed that the statistical weight of this paronic state has an upper limit of 5×10−6.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In conductors and semiconductors, there are very large numbers of molecular orbitals which effectively form a continuous band structure of energy levels.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In strong conductors (metals) electrons are so degenerate that they cannot even contribute much to the thermal capacity of a metal.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Many mechanical, electrical, magnetic, optical and chemical properties of solids are the direct consequence of Pauli exclusion.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The stability of each electron state in an atom is described by the quantum theory of the atom, which shows that close approach of an electron to the nucleus necessarily increases the electron's kinetic energy, an application of the uncertainty principle of Heisenberg.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] However, stability of large systems with many electrons and many nucleons is a different question, and requires the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] It has been shown that the Pauli exclusion principle is responsible for the fact that ordinary bulk matter is stable and occupies volume.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This suggestion was first made in 1931 by Paul Ehrenfest, who pointed out that the electrons of each atom cannot all fall into the lowest-energy orbital and must occupy successively larger shells.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Atoms, therefore, occupy a volume and cannot be squeezed too closely together.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] A much simpler proof was found later by Elliott H.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] They provided a lower bound on the quantum energy in terms of the Thomas-Fermi model, which is stable due to a theorem of Teller.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The proof used a lower bound on the kinetic energy which is now called the Lieb–Thirring inequality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The consequence of the Pauli principle here is that electrons of the same spin are kept apart by a repulsive exchange interaction, which is a short-range effect, acting simultaneously with the long-range electrostatic or Coulombic force.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This effect is partly responsible for the everyday observation in the macroscopic world that two solid objects cannot be in the same place at the same time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Dyson and Lenard did not consider the extreme magnetic or gravitational forces that occur in some astronomical objects.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In 1995 Elliott Lieb and coworkers showed that the Pauli principle still leads to stability in intense magnetic fields such as in neutron stars, although at a much higher density than in ordinary matter.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] It is a consequence of general relativity that, in sufficiently intense gravitational fields, matter collapses to form a black hole.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Astronomy provides a spectacular demonstration of the effect of the Pauli principle, in the form of white dwarf and neutron stars.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In both bodies, the atomic structure is disrupted by extreme pressure, but the stars are held in hydrostatic equilibrium by *degeneracy pressure*, also known as Fermi pressure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This exotic form of matter is known as degenerate matter.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] The immense gravitational force of a star's mass is normally held in equilibrium by thermal pressure caused by heat produced in thermonuclear fusion in the star's core.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In white dwarfs, which do not undergo nuclear fusion, an opposing force to gravity is provided by electron degeneracy pressure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] In neutron stars, subject to even stronger gravitational forces, electrons have merged with protons to form neutrons.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Neutrons are capable of producing an even higher degeneracy pressure, neutron degeneracy pressure, albeit over a shorter range.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] This can stabilize neutron stars from further collapse, but at a smaller size and higher density than a white dwarf.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] Neutron stars are the most "rigid" objects known; their Young modulus (or more accurately, bulk modulus) is 20 orders of magnitude larger than that of diamond.
[src:quantum-mechanics/pauli-exclusion-principle] However, even this enormous rigidity can be overcome by the gravitational field of a neutron star mass exceeding the Tolman–Oppenheimer–Volkoff limit, leading to the formation of a black hole.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Measurements of physical properties such as position, momentum, spin, and polarization performed on entangled particles can, in some cases, be found to be perfectly correlated.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For example, if a pair of entangled particles is generated such that their total spin is known to be zero, and one particle is found to have clockwise spin on a first axis, then the spin of the other particle, measured on the same axis, is found to be anticlockwise.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This behavior gives rise to seemingly paradoxical effects: any measurement of a particle's properties results in an apparent and irreversible wave function collapse of that particle and changes the original quantum state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] With entangled particles, such measurements affect the entangled system as a whole.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Such phenomena were the subject of a 1935 paper by Albert Einstein, Boris Podolsky, and Nathan Rosen, and several papers by Erwin Schrödinger shortly thereafter, describing what came to be known as the EPR paradox.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Einstein and others considered such behavior impossible, as it violated the local realism view of causality and argued that the accepted formulation of quantum mechanics must therefore be incomplete.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Later, the counterintuitive predictions of quantum mechanics were verified in tests where polarization or spin of entangled particles were measured at separate locations, statistically violating Bell's inequality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This established that the correlations produced from quantum entanglement cannot be explained in terms of local hidden variables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement can produce statistical correlations between events in widely separated places, but it cannot be used for faster-than-light communication.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Quantum entanglement has been demonstrated experimentally with photons, electrons, top quarks, molecules and even small diamonds.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The use of quantum entanglement in communication and computation is an active area of research and development.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Albert Einstein and Niels Bohr engaged in a long-running collegial dispute over the interpretation of quantum mechanics, now known as the Bohr–Einstein debates.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] During these debates, Einstein introduced a thought experiment involving a box that emits a photon.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] He noted that the experimenter's choice of which measurement to make on the box would change what can be predicted about the photon, even when the photon is very far away.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This argument, which Einstein had formulated by 1931, was an early recognition of what would later be called entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] That same year, Hermann Weyl observed in his textbook on group theory and quantum mechanics that quantum systems composed of multiple interacting parts exhibit a kind of *Gestalt,* in which "the whole is greater than the sum of its parts".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In 1932, Erwin Schrödinger derived the defining equations of quantum entanglement but left them unpublished.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In 1935, Grete Hermann studied the mathematics of an electron interacting with a photon and noted the phenomenon that would later be called entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Later that same year, Einstein, Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen published a paper on what is now known as the Einstein–Podolsky–Rosen (EPR) paradox, a thought experiment that attempted to show that "the quantum-mechanical description of physical reality given by wave functions is not complete".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Their thought experiment considered two systems that interact and then separate, and they argued that, afterward, quantum mechanics could not describe the two systems individually.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Shortly after this paper appeared, Erwin Schrödinger wrote a letter to Einstein in German in which he used the word *Verschränkung* (translated by himself as *entanglement*) to describe situations like that of the EPR scenario.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Einstein later disparaged quantum mechanics for seemingly exhibiting "*spukhafte Fernwirkung*", or "spooky action at a distance", meaning the acquisition of a value of a property at one location resulting from a measurement at a distant location.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In 1946, John Archibald Wheeler suggested studying the polarization of pairs of gamma-ray photons produced by electron–positron annihilation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Chien-Shiung Wu and Irving Shaknov carried out this experiment in 1949, thereby demonstrating that the entangled particle pairs considered by EPR could be created in the laboratory.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Despite Schrödinger's claim of its importance, little work on entanglement was published for decades after his paper was published.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Bell demonstrated an upper limit, seen in Bell's inequality, regarding the strength of correlations that can be produced in any theory obeying local realism, and showed that quantum theory predicts violations of this limit for certain entangled systems.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] His inequality is experimentally testable, and there have been numerous relevant experiments, starting with the pioneering work of Stuart Freedman and John Clauser in 1972, and Alain Aspect's experiments in 1982.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] While Bell actively discouraged students from pursuing work like his as too esoteric, after a talk at Oxford a student named Artur Ekert suggested that the violation of a Bell inequality could be used as a resource for communication.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Ekert followed up by publishing a quantum key distribution protocol called E91 based on it.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In 1992, the entanglement concept was leveraged to propose quantum teleportation, an effect that was realized experimentally in 1997.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Beginning in the mid-1990s, Anton Zeilinger used the generation of entanglement via parametric down-conversion to develop entanglement swapping and demonstrate quantum cryptography with entangled photons.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In 2022, the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Aspect, Clauser, and Zeilinger "for experiments with entangled photons, establishing the violation of Bell inequalities and pioneering quantum information science".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Just as energy is a resource that facilitates mechanical operations, entanglement is a resource that facilitates performing tasks that involve communication and computation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The mathematical definition of entanglement can be paraphrased as saying that maximal knowledge about the whole of a system does not imply maximal knowledge about the individual parts of that system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] If the quantum state that describes a pair of particles is entangled, then the results of measurements upon one half of the pair can be strongly correlated with the results of measurements upon the other.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] However, entanglement is not the same as "correlation" as understood in classical probability theory and in daily life.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Instead, entanglement can be thought of as *potential* correlation that can be used to generate actual correlation in an appropriate experiment.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The correlations generated from an entangled quantum state cannot in general be replicated by classical probability.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] An example of entanglement is a subatomic particle that decays into an entangled pair of other particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For instance, a spin-zero particle could decay into a pair of spin-1/2 particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] If there is no orbital angular momentum, the total spin angular momentum after this decay must be zero (by the conservation of angular momentum).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Whenever the first particle is measured to be spin up on some axis, the other, when measured on the same axis, is always found to be spin down.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This is called the spin anti-correlated case and the pair is said to be in the singlet state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Perfect anti-correlations like this could be explained by "hidden variables" within the particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For example, we could hypothesize that the particles are made in pairs such that one carries a value of "up" while the other carries a value of "down".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Then, knowing the result of the spin measurement upon one particle, we could predict that the other will have the opposite value.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Bell illustrated this with a story about a colleague, Bertlmann, who always wore socks with mismatching colors.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Quantum systems can become entangled through various types of interactions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For some ways in which entanglement may be achieved for experimental purposes, see the section below on methods.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement is broken when the entangled particles decohere through interaction with the environment; for example, when a measurement is made.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In more detail, this process involves the particles becoming entangled with the environment, as a consequence of which, the quantum state describing the particles themselves is no longer entangled.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Mathematically, an entangled system can be defined to be one whose quantum state cannot be factored as a product of states of its local constituents; that is to say, they are not individual particles but are an inseparable whole.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] When entanglement is present, one constituent cannot be fully described without considering the other(s).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The state of a composite system is always expressible as a sum, or superposition, of products of states of local constituents; it is entangled if this sum cannot be written as a single product term.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The singlet state described above is the basis for one version of the EPR paradox.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In this variant, introduced by David Bohm, a source emits particles and sends them in opposite directions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The state describing each pair is entangled.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In the standard textbook presentation of quantum mechanics, performing a spin measurement on one of the particles causes the wave function for the whole pair to collapse into a state in which each particle has a definite spin (either up or down) along the axis of measurement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The outcome is random, with each possibility having a probability of 50%.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] However, if both spins are measured along the same axis, they are found to be anti-correlated.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This means that the random outcome of the measurement made on one particle seems to have been transmitted to the other, so that it can make the "right choice" when it too is measured.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The distance and timing of the measurements can be chosen so as to make the interval between the two measurements spacelike, hence, any causal effect connecting the events would have to travel faster than light.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] According to the principles of special relativity, it is not possible for any information to travel between two such measuring events.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] It is not even possible to say which of the measurements came first.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For two spacelike separated events *x*1 and *x*2 there are inertial frames in which *x*1 is first and others in which *x*2 is first.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Therefore, the correlation between the two measurements cannot be explained as one measurement determining the other: different observers would disagree about the role of cause and effect.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] A possible resolution to the paradox is to assume that quantum theory is incomplete, and the result of measurements depends on predetermined "hidden variables".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The state of the particles being measured contains some hidden variables, whose values effectively determine, right from the moment of separation, what the outcomes of the spin measurements are going to be.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This would mean that each particle carries all the required information with it, and nothing needs to be transmitted from one particle to the other at the time of measurement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Einstein and others originally believed this was the only way out of the paradox, and the accepted quantum mechanical description (with a random measurement outcome) must be incomplete.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Local hidden variable theories fail when measurements of the spin of entangled particles along different axes are considered.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] If a large number of pairs of such measurements are made (on a large number of pairs of entangled particles), then statistically, if the local realist or hidden variables view were correct, the results would always satisfy Bell's inequality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] A number of experiments have shown in practice that Bell's inequality is not satisfied.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Moreover, when measurements of the entangled particles are made in moving relativistic reference frames, in which each measurement (in its own relativistic time frame) occurs before the other, the measurement results remain correlated.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The fundamental issue about measuring spin along different axes is that these measurements cannot have definite values at the same time―they are incompatible in the sense that these measurements' maximum simultaneous precision is constrained by the uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This is contrary to what is found in classical physics, where any number of properties can be measured simultaneously with arbitrary accuracy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] It has been proven mathematically that compatible measurements cannot show Bell-inequality-violating correlations, and thus entanglement is a fundamentally non-classical phenomenon.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] As discussed above, entanglement is necessary to produce a violation of a Bell inequality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] However, the mere presence of entanglement alone is insufficient, as Bell himself noted in his 1964 paper.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This is demonstrated, for example, by Werner states, which are a family of states describing pairs of particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For appropriate choices of the key parameter that identifies a given Werner state within the full set thereof, the Werner states exhibit entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Yet pairs of particles described by Werner states always admit a local hidden variable model.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In other words, these states cannot power the violation of a Bell inequality, despite possessing entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This can be generalized from pairs of particles to larger collections as well.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The violation of Bell inequalities is often called *quantum nonlocality.* This term is not without controversy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] It is sometimes argued that using the term *nonlocality* carries the unwarranted implication that the violation of Bell inequalities must be explained by physical, faster-than-light signals.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In other words, the failure of local hidden-variable models to reproduce quantum mechanics is not necessarily a sign of true nonlocality in quantum mechanics itself.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Despite these reservations, the term *nonlocality* has become a widespread convention.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The term *nonlocality* is sometimes applied to other concepts besides the nonexistence of a local hidden-variable model, such as whether states can be distinguished by local measurements.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Moreover, quantum field theory is often said to be *local* because observables defined within spacetime regions that are spacelike separated must commute.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] These other uses of *local* and *nonlocal* are not discussed further here.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The following subsections use the formalism and theoretical framework developed in the articles bra–ket notation and mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Consider two arbitrary quantum systems A and B, with respective Hilbert spaces HA and HB.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] States of the composite system that can be represented in this form are called separable states, or product states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] However, not all states of the composite system are separable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] If the composite system is in this state, it is impossible to attribute to either system A or system B a definite pure state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Another way to say this is that while the von Neumann entropy of the whole state is zero (as it is for any pure state), the entropy of the subsystems is greater than zero.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In this sense, the systems are "entangled".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The above example is one of four Bell states, which are (maximally) entangled pure states (pure states of the *HA* ⊗ *HB* space, but which cannot be separated into pure states of each HA and HB).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Now suppose Alice is an observer for system A, and Bob is an observer for system B.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] If in the entangled state given above Alice makes a measurement in the $\{|0\rangle ,|1\rangle \}$ eigenbasis of A, there are two possible outcomes, occurring with equal probability: Alice can obtain the outcome 0, or she can obtain the outcome 1.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] If she obtains the outcome 0, then she can predict with certainty that Bob's result will be 1.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Likewise, if she obtains the outcome 1, then she can predict with certainty that Bob's result will be 0.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In other words, the results of measurements on the two qubits will be perfectly anti-correlated.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This remains true even if the systems A and B are spatially separated.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This is the foundation of the EPR paradox.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The outcome of Alice's measurement is random.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Alice cannot decide which state to collapse the composite system into, and therefore cannot transmit information to Bob by acting on her system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Causality is thus preserved, in this particular scheme.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For the general argument, see no-communication theorem.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] As mentioned above, a state of a quantum system is given by a unit vector in a Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] More generally, if one has less information about the system, then one calls it an 'ensemble' and describes it by a density matrix, which is a positive-semidefinite matrix, or a trace class when the state space is infinite-dimensional, and which has trace 1.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] where the *w**i* are positive-valued probabilities (they sum up to 1), the vectors *α**i* are unit vectors, and in the infinite-dimensional case, we would take the closure of such states in the trace norm.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] We can interpret ρ as representing an ensemble where $w_{i}$ is the proportion of the ensemble whose states are $|\alpha _{i}\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] When a mixed state has rank 1, it therefore describes a 'pure ensemble'.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] When there is less than total information about the state of a quantum system we need density matrices to represent the state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Experimentally, a mixed ensemble might be realized as follows.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Consider a "black box" apparatus that spits electrons towards an observer.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The electrons' Hilbert spaces are identical.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The apparatus might produce electrons that are all in the same state; in this case, the electrons received by the observer are then a pure ensemble.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] However, the apparatus could produce electrons in different states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For example, it could produce two populations of electrons: one with state $|\mathbf {z} +\rangle$ with spins aligned in the positive **z** direction, and the other with state $|\mathbf {y} -\rangle$ with spins aligned in the negative **y** direction.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Generally, this is a mixed ensemble, as there can be any number of populations, each corresponding to a different state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Following the definition above, for a bipartite composite system, mixed states are just density matrices on *HA* ⊗ *HB*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] where the *w**i* are positively valued probabilities, ${\textstyle \sum _{j}|c_{ij}|^{2}=1}$ , and the vectors are unit vectors.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This is self-adjoint and positive and has trace 1.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] where the *w**i* are positively valued probabilities and the $\rho _{i}^{A}$ s and $\rho _{i}^{B}$ s are themselves mixed states (density operators) on the subsystems A and B respectively.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In other words, a state is separable if it is a probability distribution over uncorrelated states, or product states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] By writing the density matrices as sums of pure ensembles and expanding, we may assume without loss of generality that $\rho _{i}^{A}$ and $\rho _{i}^{B}$ are themselves pure ensembles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] A state is then said to be entangled if it is not separable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In general, finding out whether or not a mixed state is entangled is considered difficult.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The general bipartite case has been shown to be NP-hard.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For the 2 × 2 and 2 × 3 cases, a necessary and sufficient criterion for separability is given by the famous Positive Partial Transpose (PPT) condition.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The idea of a reduced density matrix was introduced by Paul Dirac in 1930.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Consider as above systems A and B each with a Hilbert space HA, HB.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] As indicated above, in general there is no way to associate a pure state to the component system A.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] However, it still is possible to associate a density matrix.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] which is the projection operator onto this state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The sum occurs over $N_{B}:=\dim(H_{B})$ and $I_{A}$ the identity operator in $H_{A}$ . ρA is sometimes called the reduced density matrix of ρ on subsystem A.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Colloquially, we "trace out" or "trace over" system B to obtain the reduced density matrix on A.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This demonstrates that the reduced density matrix for an entangled pure ensemble is a mixed ensemble.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] the projection operator onto $|\psi \rangle _{A}$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In general, a bipartite pure state *ρ* is entangled if and only if its reduced states are mixed rather than pure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In quantum information theory, entangled states are considered a 'resource', i.e., something costly to produce and that allows implementing valuable transformations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The setting in which this perspective is most evident is that of "distant labs", i.e., two quantum systems labelled "A" and "B" on each of which arbitrary quantum operations can be performed, but which do not interact with each other quantum mechanically.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The only interaction allowed is the exchange of classical information, which combined with the most general local quantum operations gives rise to the class of operations called LOCC (local operations and classical communication).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] These operations do not allow the production of entangled states between systems A and B.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] But if A and B are provided with a supply of entangled states, then these, together with LOCC operations can enable a larger class of transformations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] If Alice and Bob share an entangled state, Alice can tell Bob over a telephone call how to reproduce a quantum state $|\Psi \rangle$ she has in her lab.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Alice performs a joint measurement on $|\Psi \rangle$ together with her half of the entangled state and tells Bob the results.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Using Alice's results Bob operates on his half of the entangled state to make it equal to $|\Psi \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Since Alice's measurement necessarily erases the quantum state of the system in her lab, the state $|\Psi \rangle$ is not copied, but transferred: it is said to be "teleported" to Bob's laboratory through this protocol.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement swapping is variant of teleportation that allows two parties that have never interacted to share an entangled state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The swapping protocol begins with two EPR sources.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] One source emits an entangled pair of particles A and B, while the other emits a second entangled pair of particles C and D.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Particles B and C are subjected to a measurement in the basis of Bell states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The state of the remaining particles, A and D, collapses to a Bell state, leaving them entangled despite never having interacted with each other.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] An interaction between a qubit of A and a qubit of B can be realized by first teleporting A's qubit to B, then letting it interact with B's qubit (which is now a LOCC operation, since both qubits are in B's lab) and then teleporting the qubit back to A.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Two maximally entangled states of two qubits are used up in this process.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Thus entangled states are a resource that enables the realization of quantum interactions (or of quantum channels) in a setting where only LOCC are available, but they are consumed in the process.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] There are other applications where entanglement can be seen as a resource, e.g., private communication or distinguishing quantum states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Quantum states describing systems made of more than two pieces can also be entangled.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This illustrates how multipartite entanglement is a more complicated topic than bipartite entanglement: systems composed of three or more parts can exhibit multiple qualitatively different types of entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] A single particle cannot be maximally entangled with more than a particle at a time, a property called monogamy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Not all quantum states are equally valuable as a resource.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] One method to quantify this value is to use an entanglement measure that assigns a numerical value to each quantum state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] However, it is often interesting to settle for a coarser way to compare quantum states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This gives rise to different classification schemes.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Most entanglement classes are defined based on whether states can be converted to other states using LOCC or a subclass of these operations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The smaller the set of allowed operations, the finer the classification.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In this section, the entropy of a mixed state is discussed as well as how it can be viewed as a measure of quantum entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] When a pair of particles is described by the spin singlet state discussed above, the von Neumann entropy of either particle is log(2), which can be shown to be the maximum entropy for 2 × 2 mixed states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Entropy provides one tool that can be used to quantify entanglement, although other entanglement measures exist.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] If the overall system is pure, the entropy of one subsystem can be used to measure its degree of entanglement with the other subsystems.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For bipartite pure states, the von Neumann entropy of reduced states is the unique measure of entanglement in the sense that it is the only function on the family of states that satisfies certain axioms required of an entanglement measure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] It is a classical result that the Shannon entropy achieves its maximum at, and only at, the uniform probability distribution {1/*n*, ..., 1/*n*}.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For mixed states, the reduced von Neumann entropy is not the only reasonable entanglement measure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Rényi entropy can be used as a measure of entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement measures quantify the amount of entanglement in a (often viewed as a bipartite) quantum state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] As aforementioned, entanglement entropy is the standard measure of entanglement for pure states (but no longer a measure of entanglement for mixed states).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For mixed states, there are some entanglement measures in the literature and no single one is standard.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Most (but not all) of these entanglement measures reduce for pure states to entanglement entropy, and are difficult (NP-hard) to compute for mixed states as the dimension of the entangled system grows.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The Reeh–Schlieder theorem of quantum field theory is sometimes interpreted as saying that entanglement is omnipresent in the quantum vacuum.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement has many applications in quantum information theory.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] With the aid of entanglement, otherwise impossible tasks may be achieved.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Among the best-known applications of entanglement are superdense coding and quantum teleportation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Most researchers believe that entanglement is necessary to realize quantum computing (although this is disputed by some).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement is used in some protocols of quantum cryptography, but to prove the security of quantum key distribution (QKD) under standard assumptions does not require entanglement; however, the *device independent* security of QKD is shown exploiting entanglement between the communication partners.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In August 2014, Brazilian researcher Gabriela Barreto Lemos, from the University of Vienna, and team were able to "take pictures" of objects using photons that had not interacted with the subjects, but were entangled with photons that did interact with such objects.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The idea has been adapted to make infrared images using only standard cameras that are insensitive to infrared.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] There are several canonical entangled states that appear often in theory and experiments.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] These four pure states are all maximally entangled and form an orthonormal basis of the Hilbert space of the two qubits.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] They provide examples of how quantum mechanics can violate Bell-type inequalities.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] which reduces to the Bell state $|\Phi ^{+}\rangle$ for *M* = 2.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The traditional GHZ state was defined for *M* = 3.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] GHZ states are occasionally extended to qudits, i.e., systems of *d* rather than 2 dimensions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Also for *M* > 2 qubits, there are spin squeezed states, a class of squeezed coherent states satisfying certain restrictions on the uncertainty of spin measurements, which are necessarily entangled.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Spin squeezed states are good candidates for enhancing precision measurements using quantum entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This is like the Bell state $|\Psi ^{+}\rangle$ except the basis states $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ have been replaced with "the *N* photons are in one mode" and "the *N* photons are in the other mode".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Finally, there also exist twin Fock states for bosonic modes, which can be created by feeding a Fock state into two arms leading to a beam splitter.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] They are the sum of multiple NOON states, and can be used to achieve the Heisenberg limit.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For the appropriately chosen measures of entanglement, Bell, GHZ, and NOON states are maximally entangled while spin squeezed and twin Fock states are only partially entangled.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement is usually created by direct interactions between subatomic particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] These interactions can take numerous forms.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] One of the most commonly used methods is spontaneous parametric down-conversion to generate a pair of photons entangled in polarization.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Other methods include the use of a fiber coupler to confine and mix photons, photons emitted from decay cascade of the bi-exciton in a quantum dot, or the use of the Hong–Ou–Mandel effect.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Quantum entanglement of a particle and its antiparticle, such as an electron and a positron, can be created by partial overlap of the corresponding quantum wave functions in Hardy's interferometer.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In the earliest tests of Bell's theorem, the entangled particles were generated using atomic cascades.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] It is also possible to create entanglement between quantum systems that never directly interacted, through the use of entanglement swapping.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Two independently prepared, identical particles may also be entangled if their wave functions merely spatially overlap, at least partially.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] A density matrix *ρ* is called separable if it can be written as a convex sum of product states, namely ${\rho =\sum _{j}p_{j}\rho _{j}^{(A)}\otimes \rho _{j}^{(B)}}$ with $0\leq p_{j}\leq 1$ probabilities.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] By definition, a state is entangled if it is not separable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] For 2-qubit and qubit-qutrit systems (2 × 2 and 2 × 3 respectively) the simple Peres–Horodecki criterion provides both a necessary and a sufficient criterion for separability, and thus—inadvertently—for detecting entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] However, for the general case, the criterion is merely a necessary one for separability, as the problem becomes NP-hard when generalized.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Other separability criteria include (but not limited to) the range criterion, reduction criterion, and those based on uncertainty relations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] See Ref. for a review of separability criteria in discrete-variable systems and Ref. for a review on techniques and challenges in experimental entanglement certification in discrete-variable systems.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] A numerical approach to the problem is suggested by Jon Magne Leinaas, Jan Myrheim and Eirik Ovrum in their paper "Geometrical aspects of entanglement".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Leinaas et al. offer a numerical approach, iteratively refining an estimated separable state towards the target state to be tested, and checking if the target state can indeed be reached.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In continuous variable systems, the Peres–Horodecki criterion also applies.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] It was later found that Simon's condition is also necessary and sufficient for $1\oplus n$ -mode Gaussian states, but no longer sufficient for $2\oplus 2$ -mode Gaussian states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Simon's condition can be generalized by taking into account the higher order moments of canonical operators or by using entropic measures.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] There is a fundamental conflict, referred to as the problem of time, between the way the concept of *time* is used in quantum mechanics, and the role it plays in general relativity.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In standard quantum theories time acts as an independent background through which states evolve, while general relativity treats time as a dynamical variable which relates directly with matter.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Part of the effort to reconcile these approaches to time results in the Wheeler–DeWitt equation, which predicts the state of the universe is timeless or static, contrary to ordinary experience.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Work started by Don Page and William Wootters suggests that the universe appears to evolve for observers on the inside because of energy entanglement between an evolving system and a clock system, both within the universe.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In this way the overall system can remain timeless while parts experience time via entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The issue remains an open question closely related to attempts at theories of quantum gravity.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In general relativity, gravity arises from the curvature of spacetime and that curvature derives from the distribution of matter.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] However, matter is governed by quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Integration of these two theories faces many problems.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In an (unrealistic) model space called the anti-de Sitter space, the AdS/CFT correspondence allows a quantum gravitational system to be related to a quantum field theory without gravity.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Using this correspondence, Mark Van Raamsdonk suggested that spacetime arises as an emergent phenomenon of the quantum degrees of freedom that are entangled and live in the boundary of the spacetime.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] A Bell test, also known as *Bell inequality test* or *Bell experiment*, is a real-world physics experiment designed to test the theory of quantum mechanics against the hypothesis of local hidden variables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] These tests empirically evaluate the implications of Bell's theorem.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] To date, all Bell tests have found that the hypothesis of local hidden variables is inconsistent with the way that physical systems behave.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Many types of Bell tests have been performed in physics laboratories, often with the goal of ameliorating problems of experimental design or set-up that could in principle affect the validity of the findings of earlier Bell tests.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] This is known as "closing loopholes in Bell tests".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In 2023 the LHC using techniques from quantum tomography measured entanglement at the highest energy so far, a rare intersection between quantum information and high energy physics based on theoretical work first proposed in 2021.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] The spin polarization and correlation of the particles was measured and tested for entanglement with concurrence as well as the Peres–Horodecki criterion and subsequently the effect has been confirmed too in the CMS detector.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] In 2020, researchers reported the quantum entanglement between the motion of a millimetre-sized mechanical oscillator and a disparate distant spin system of a cloud of atoms.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Later work complemented this work by quantum-entangling two mechanical oscillators.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Physicists at Brookhaven National Laboratory demonstrated quantum entanglement within protons, showing quarks and gluons are interdependent rather than isolated particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-entanglement] Using high-energy electron-proton collisions, they revealed maximal entanglement, reshaping our understanding of proton structure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum mechanics can describe many systems that classical physics cannot.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Classical physics can describe many aspects of nature at an ordinary (macroscopic and (optical) microscopic) scale; however, it is insufficient for describing them at very small submicroscopic (atomic and subatomic) scales.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Classical mechanics can be derived from quantum mechanics as an approximation that is valid at ordinary scales.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] These early attempts to understand microscopic phenomena, now known as the "old quantum theory", led to the full development of quantum mechanics in the mid-1920s by Niels Bohr, Erwin Schrödinger, Werner Heisenberg, Max Born, Paul Dirac and others.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The modern theory is formulated in various specially developed mathematical formalisms.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In one of them, a mathematical entity called the wave function provides information, in the form of probability amplitudes, about what measurements of a particle's energy, momentum, and other physical properties may yield.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum mechanics allows the calculation of properties and behaviour of physical systems.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] It is typically applied to microscopic systems: molecules, atoms and subatomic particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] It has been demonstrated to hold for complex molecules with thousands of atoms, but its application to human beings raises philosophical problems, such as Wigner's friend, and its application to the universe as a whole remains speculative.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Predictions of quantum mechanics have been verified experimentally to an extremely high degree of accuracy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] For example, the refinement of quantum mechanics for the interaction of light and matter, known as quantum electrodynamics (QED), has been shown to agree with experiment to within 1 part in 1012 when predicting the magnetic properties of an electron.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] A fundamental feature of the theory is that it usually cannot predict with certainty what will happen, but only gives probabilities.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Mathematically, a probability is found by taking the square of the absolute value of a complex number, known as a probability amplitude.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This is known as the Born rule, named after physicist Max Born.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] For example, a quantum particle like an electron can be described by a wave function, which associates to each point in space a probability amplitude.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Applying the Born rule to these amplitudes gives a probability density function for the position that the electron will be found to have when an experiment is performed to measure it.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This is the best the theory can do; it cannot say for certain where the electron will be found.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The Schrödinger equation relates the collection of probability amplitudes that pertain to one moment of time to the collection of probability amplitudes that pertain to another.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] One consequence of the mathematical rules of quantum mechanics is a tradeoff in predictability between measurable quantities.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The most famous form of this uncertainty principle says that no matter how a quantum particle is prepared or how carefully experiments upon it are arranged, it is impossible to have a precise prediction for a measurement of its position and also at the same time for a measurement of its momentum.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Another consequence of the mathematical rules of quantum mechanics is the phenomenon of quantum interference, which is often illustrated with the double-slit experiment.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In the basic version of this experiment, a coherent light source, such as a laser beam, illuminates a plate pierced by two parallel slits, and the light passing through the slits is observed on a screen behind the plate.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The wave nature of light causes the light waves passing through the two slits to interfere, producing bright and dark bands on the screen – a result that would not be expected if light consisted of classical particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] However, the light is always found to be absorbed at the screen at discrete points, as individual particles rather than waves; the interference pattern appears via the varying density of these particle hits on the screen.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Furthermore, versions of the experiment that include detectors at the slits find that each detected photon passes through one slit (as would a classical particle), and not through both slits (as would a wave).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] However, such experiments demonstrate that particles do not form the interference pattern if one detects which slit they pass through.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This behavior is known as wave–particle duality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In addition to light, electrons, atoms, and molecules are all found to exhibit the same dual behavior when fired towards a double slit.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Another non-classical phenomenon predicted by quantum mechanics is quantum tunnelling: a particle that goes up against a potential barrier can cross it, even if its kinetic energy is smaller than the maximum of the potential.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In classical mechanics this particle would be trapped.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum tunnelling has several important consequences, enabling radioactive decay, nuclear fusion in stars, and applications such as scanning tunnelling microscopy, tunnel diode and tunnel field-effect transistor.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] When quantum systems interact, the result can be the creation of quantum entanglement: their properties become so intertwined that a description of the whole solely in terms of the individual parts is no longer possible.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Erwin Schrödinger called entanglement "...*the* characteristic trait of quantum mechanics, the one that enforces its entire departure from classical lines of thought".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum entanglement enables quantum computing and is part of quantum communication protocols, such as quantum key distribution and superdense coding.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Contrary to popular misconception, entanglement does not allow sending signals faster than light, as demonstrated by the no-communication theorem.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Another possibility opened by entanglement is testing for "hidden variables", hypothetical properties more fundamental than the quantities addressed in quantum theory itself, knowledge of which would allow more exact predictions than quantum theory provides.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] A collection of results, most significantly Bell's theorem, have demonstrated that broad classes of such hidden-variable theories are in fact incompatible with quantum physics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] According to Bell's theorem, if nature actually operates in accord with any theory of *local* hidden variables, then the results of a Bell test will be constrained in a particular, quantifiable way.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Many Bell tests have been performed and they have shown results incompatible with the constraints imposed by local hidden variables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] It is not possible to present these concepts in more than a superficial way without introducing the mathematics involved; understanding quantum mechanics requires not only manipulating complex numbers, but also linear algebra, differential equations, group theory, and other more advanced subjects.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Accordingly, this article will present a mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics and survey its application to some useful and oft-studied examples.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In the mathematically rigorous formulation of quantum mechanics, the state of a quantum mechanical system is a vector $\psi$ belonging to a (separable) complex Hilbert space ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This vector is postulated to be normalized under the Hilbert space inner product, that is, it obeys $\langle \psi ,\psi \rangle =1$ , and it is well-defined up to a complex number of modulus 1 (the global phase), that is, $\psi$ and $e^{i\alpha }\psi$ represent the same physical system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In other words, the possible states are points in the projective space of a Hilbert space, usually called the complex projective space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Physical quantities of interest – position, momentum, energy, spin – are represented by observables, which are Hermitian (more precisely, self-adjoint) linear operators acting on the Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] A quantum state can be an eigenvector of an observable, in which case it is called an eigenstate, and the associated eigenvalue corresponds to the value of the observable in that eigenstate.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] More generally, a quantum state will be a linear combination of the eigenstates, known as a quantum superposition.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] More generally, the eigenvalue is degenerate and the probability is given by $\langle \psi ,P_{\lambda }\psi \rangle$ , where $P_{\lambda }$ is the projector onto its associated eigenspace.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In the continuous case, these formulas give instead the probability density.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] After the measurement, if result $\lambda$ was obtained, the quantum state is postulated to collapse to ${\vec {\lambda }}$ , in the non-degenerate case, or to ${\textstyle P_{\lambda }\psi {\big /}\!{\sqrt {\langle \psi ,P_{\lambda }\psi \rangle }}}$ , in the general case.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The probabilistic nature of quantum mechanics thus stems from the act of measurement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This is one of the most debated aspects of quantum theory, with different interpretations of quantum mechanics giving radically different answers to questions regarding quantum-state collapse, as discussed below.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The time evolution of a quantum state is described by the Schrödinger equation: $i\hbar {\frac {\partial }{\partial t}}\psi (t)=H\psi (t).$ Here H denotes the Hamiltonian, the observable corresponding to the total energy of the system, and $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The constant $i\hbar$ is introduced so that the Hamiltonian is reduced to the classical Hamiltonian in cases where the quantum system can be approximated by a classical system; the ability to make such an approximation in certain limits is called the correspondence principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The solution of this differential equation is given by $\psi (t)=e^{-iHt/\hbar }\psi (0).$ The operator $U(t)=e^{-iHt/\hbar }$ is known as the time-evolution operator, and has the crucial property that it is unitary.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This time evolution is deterministic in the sense that – given an initial quantum state $\psi (0)$ – it makes a definite prediction of what the quantum state $\psi (t)$ will be at any later time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Some wave functions produce probability distributions that are independent of time, such as eigenstates of the Hamiltonian.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Many systems that are treated dynamically in classical mechanics are described by such "static" wave functions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] For example, a single electron in an unexcited atom is pictured classically as a particle moving in a circular trajectory around the atomic nucleus, whereas in quantum mechanics, it is described by a static wave function surrounding the nucleus.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] For example, the electron wave function for an unexcited hydrogen atom is a spherically symmetric function known as an *s* orbital (Fig.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Analytic solutions of the Schrödinger equation are known for very few relatively simple model Hamiltonians including the quantum harmonic oscillator, the particle in a box, the dihydrogen cation, and the hydrogen atom.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Even the helium atom – which contains just two electrons – has defied all attempts at a fully analytic treatment, admitting no solution in closed form.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] However, there are techniques for finding approximate solutions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] One method, called perturbation theory, uses the analytic result for a simple quantum mechanical model to create a result for a related but more complicated model by (for example) the addition of a weak potential energy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Another approximation method applies to systems for which quantum mechanics produces only small deviations from classical behavior.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] These deviations can then be computed based on the classical motion.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] One consequence of the basic quantum formalism is the uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In its most familiar form, this states that no preparation of a quantum particle can imply simultaneously precise predictions both for a measurement of its position and for a measurement of its momentum.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Both position and momentum are observables, meaning that they are represented by Hermitian operators.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The position operator ${\hat {X}}$ and momentum operator ${\hat {P}}$ do not commute, but rather satisfy the canonical commutation relation: $[{\hat {X}},{\hat {P}}]=i\hbar .$ Given a quantum state, the Born rule lets us compute expectation values for both X and P , and moreover for powers of them.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This inequality generalizes to arbitrary pairs of self-adjoint operators A and B .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Another consequence of the canonical commutation relation is that the position and momentum operators are Fourier transforms of each other, so that a description of an object according to its momentum is the Fourier transform of its description according to its position.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This is why in quantum equations in position space, the momentum $p_{i}$ is replaced by $-i\hbar {\frac {\partial }{\partial x}}$ , and in particular in the non-relativistic Schrödinger equation in position space the momentum-squared term is replaced with a Laplacian times $-\hbar ^{2}$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] When two different quantum systems are considered together, the Hilbert space of the combined system is the tensor product of the Hilbert spaces of the two components.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] For example, let A and B be two quantum systems, with Hilbert spaces ${\mathcal {H}}_{A}$ and ${\mathcal {H}}_{B}$ , respectively.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] States that are not separable are called entangled.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] If the state for a composite system is entangled, it is impossible to describe either component system A or system B by a state vector.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] One can instead define reduced density matrices that describe the statistics that can be obtained by making measurements on either component system alone.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This necessarily causes a loss of information, though: knowing the reduced density matrices of the individual systems is not enough to reconstruct the state of the composite system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Just as density matrices specify the state of a subsystem of a larger system, analogously, positive operator-valued measures (POVMs) describe the effect on a subsystem of a measurement performed on a larger system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] POVMs are extensively used in quantum information theory.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] As described above, entanglement is a key feature of models of measurement processes in which an apparatus becomes entangled with the system being measured.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Systems interacting with the environment in which they reside generally become entangled with that environment, a phenomenon known as quantum decoherence.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This can explain why, in practice, quantum effects are difficult to observe in systems larger than microscopic.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] There are many mathematically equivalent formulations of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] One of the oldest and most common is the "transformation theory" proposed by Paul Dirac, which unifies and generalizes the two earliest formulations of quantum mechanics – matrix mechanics (invented by Werner Heisenberg) and wave mechanics (invented by Erwin Schrödinger).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] An alternative formulation of quantum mechanics is Feynman's path integral formulation, in which a quantum-mechanical amplitude is considered as a sum over all possible classical and non-classical paths between the initial and final states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This is the quantum-mechanical counterpart of the action principle in classical mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The Hamiltonian H is known as the *generator* of time evolution, since it defines a unitary time-evolution operator $U(t)=e^{-iHt/\hbar }$ for each value of t .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] From this relation between $U(t)$ and H , it follows that any observable A that commutes with H will be *conserved*: its expectation value will not change over time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This statement generalizes, as mathematically, any Hermitian operator A can generate a family of unitary operators parameterized by a variable t .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Under the evolution generated by A , any observable B that commutes with A will be conserved.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Moreover, if B is conserved by evolution under A , then A is conserved under the evolution generated by B .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This implies a quantum version of the result proven by Emmy Noether in classical (Lagrangian) mechanics: for every differentiable symmetry of a Hamiltonian, there exists a corresponding conservation law.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The simplest example of a quantum system with a position degree of freedom is a free particle in a single spatial dimension.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The coefficients of the superposition are ${\hat {\psi }}(k,0)$ , which is the Fourier transform of the initial quantum state $\psi (x,0)$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] It is not possible for the solution to be a single momentum eigenstate, or a single position eigenstate, as these are not normalizable quantum states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Conversely, by making a larger we make the spread in momentum smaller, but the spread in position gets larger.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This illustrates the uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] As we let the Gaussian wave packet evolve in time, we see that its center moves through space at a constant velocity (like a classical particle with no forces acting on it).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] However, the wave packet will also spread out as time progresses, which means that the position becomes more and more uncertain.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The uncertainty in momentum, however, stays constant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The particle in a one-dimensional potential energy box is the most mathematically simple example where restraints lead to the quantization of energy levels.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The box is defined as having zero potential energy everywhere *inside* a certain region, and therefore infinite potential energy everywhere *outside* that region.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] With the differential operator defined by ${\hat {p}}_{x}=-i\hbar {\frac {d}{dx}}$ the previous equation is evocative of the classic kinetic energy analogue, ${\frac {1}{2m}}{\hat {p}}_{x}^{2}=E,$ with state $\psi$ in this case having energy E coincident with the kinetic energy of the particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The infinite potential walls of the box determine the values of $C,D,$ and k at $x=0$ and $x=L$ where $\psi$ must be zero.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] At $x=L$ , $\psi (L)=0=C\sin(kL),$ in which C cannot be zero as this would conflict with the postulate that $\psi$ has norm 1.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] A finite potential well is the generalization of the infinite potential well problem to potential wells having finite depth.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The finite potential well problem is mathematically more complicated than the infinite particle-in-a-box problem as the wave function is not pinned to zero at the walls of the well.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Instead, the wave function must satisfy more complicated mathematical boundary conditions as it is nonzero in regions outside the well.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Another related problem is that of the rectangular potential barrier, which furnishes a model for the quantum tunneling effect that plays an important role in the performance of modern technologies such as flash memory and scanning tunneling microscopy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This problem can either be treated by directly solving the Schrödinger equation, which is not trivial, or by using the more elegant "ladder method" first proposed by Paul Dirac.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This is another example illustrating the discretization of energy for bound states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The Mach–Zehnder interferometer (MZI) illustrates the concepts of superposition and interference with linear algebra in dimension 2, rather than differential equations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] It can be seen as a simplified version of the double-slit experiment, but it is of interest in its own right, for example in the delayed choice quantum eraser, the Elitzur–Vaidman bomb tester, and in studies of quantum entanglement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In order to respect the postulate that $\langle \psi ,\psi \rangle =1$ we require that $|\alpha |^{2}+|\beta |^{2}=1$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The phase shifter on the upper arm is modelled as the unitary matrix $P={\begin{pmatrix}1&0\\0&e^{i\Delta \Phi }\end{pmatrix}}$ , which means that if the photon is on the "upper" path it will gain a relative phase of $\Delta \Phi$ , and it will stay unchanged if it is in the lower path.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] It is interesting to consider what would happen if the photon were definitely in either the "lower" or "upper" paths between the beam splitters.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This can be accomplished by blocking one of the paths, or equivalently by removing the first beam splitter (and feeding the photon from the left or the bottom, as desired).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In both cases, there will be no interference between the paths anymore, and the probabilities are given by $p(u)=p(l)=1/2$ , independently of the phase $\Delta \Phi$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] From this we can conclude that the photon does not take one path or another after the first beam splitter, but rather that it is in a genuine quantum superposition of the two paths.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum mechanics has had enormous success in explaining many of the features of our universe, with regard to small-scale and discrete quantities and interactions which cannot be explained by classical methods.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum mechanics is often the only theory that can reveal the individual behaviors of the subatomic particles that make up all forms of matter (electrons, protons, neutrons, photons, and others).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Solid-state physics and materials science are dependent upon quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In many aspects, modern technology operates at a scale where quantum effects are significant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Explanations for many biological and physical phenomena are rooted in the nature of the chemical bond, most notably the macro-molecule DNA.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The rules of quantum mechanics assert that the state space of a system is a Hilbert space and that observables of the system are Hermitian operators acting on vectors in that space – although they do not tell us which Hilbert space or which operators.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] These can be chosen appropriately in order to obtain a quantitative description of a quantum system, a necessary step in making physical predictions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] An important guide for making these choices is the correspondence principle, a heuristic which states that the predictions of quantum mechanics reduce to those of classical mechanics in the regime of large quantum numbers.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] One can also start from an established classical model of a particular system, and then try to guess the underlying quantum model that would give rise to the classical model in the correspondence limit.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] When quantum mechanics was originally formulated, it was applied to models whose correspondence limit was non-relativistic classical mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] For instance, the well-known model of the quantum harmonic oscillator uses an explicitly non-relativistic expression for the kinetic energy of the oscillator, and is thus a quantum version of the classical harmonic oscillator.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Complications arise with chaotic systems, which do not have good quantum numbers, and quantum chaos studies the relationship between classical and quantum descriptions in these systems.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum decoherence is a mechanism through which quantum systems lose coherence, and thus become incapable of displaying many typically quantum effects: quantum superpositions become simply probabilistic mixtures, and quantum entanglement becomes simply classical correlations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum coherence is not typically evident at macroscopic scales, though at temperatures approaching absolute zero quantum behavior may manifest macroscopically.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Many macroscopic properties of a classical system are a direct consequence of the quantum behavior of its parts.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Early attempts to merge quantum mechanics with special relativity involved the replacement of the Schrödinger equation with a covariant equation such as the Klein–Gordon equation or the Dirac equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] While these theories were successful in explaining many experimental results, they had certain unsatisfactory qualities stemming from their neglect of the relativistic creation and annihilation of particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] A fully relativistic quantum theory required the development of quantum field theory, which applies quantization to a field (rather than a fixed set of particles).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The first complete quantum field theory, quantum electrodynamics, provides a fully quantum description of the electromagnetic interaction.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum electrodynamics is, along with general relativity, one of the most accurate physical theories ever devised.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The full apparatus of quantum field theory is often unnecessary for describing electrodynamic systems.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] A simpler approach, one that has been used since the inception of quantum mechanics, is to treat charged particles as quantum mechanical objects being acted on by a classical electromagnetic field.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] For example, the elementary quantum model of the hydrogen atom describes the electric field of the hydrogen atom using a classical $\textstyle -e^{2}/(4\pi \epsilon _{_{0}}r)$ Coulomb potential.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Likewise, in a Stern–Gerlach experiment, a charged particle is modeled as a quantum system, while the background magnetic field is described classically.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This "semi-classical" approach fails if quantum fluctuations in the electromagnetic field play an important role, such as in the emission of photons by charged particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum field theories for the strong nuclear force and the weak nuclear force have also been developed.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The quantum field theory of the strong nuclear force is called quantum chromodynamics, and describes the interactions of subnuclear particles such as quarks and gluons.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The weak nuclear force and the electromagnetic force were unified, in their quantized forms, into a single quantum field theory (known as electroweak theory), by the physicists Abdus Salam, Sheldon Glashow and Steven Weinberg.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Even though the predictions of both quantum theory and general relativity have been supported by rigorous and repeated empirical evidence, their abstract formalisms contradict each other and they have proven extremely difficult to incorporate into one consistent, cohesive model.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Gravity is negligible in many areas of particle physics, so that unification between general relativity and quantum mechanics is not an urgent issue in those particular applications.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] However, the lack of a correct theory of quantum gravity is an important issue in physical cosmology and the search by physicists for an elegant "Theory of Everything" (TOE).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Consequently, resolving the inconsistencies between both theories has been a major goal of 20th- and 21st-century physics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This TOE would combine not only the models of subatomic physics but also derive the four fundamental forces of nature from a single force or phenomenon.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] One proposal for doing so is string theory, which posits that the point-like particles of particle physics are replaced by one-dimensional objects called strings.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] String theory describes how these strings propagate through space and interact with each other.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] On distance scales larger than the string scale, a string looks just like an ordinary particle, with its mass, charge, and other properties determined by the vibrational state of the string.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In string theory, one of the many vibrational states of the string corresponds to the graviton, a quantum mechanical particle that carries gravitational force.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Another popular theory is loop quantum gravity (LQG), which describes quantum properties of gravity and is thus a theory of quantum spacetime.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] LQG is an attempt to merge and adapt standard quantum mechanics and standard general relativity.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This theory describes space as an extremely fine fabric "woven" of finite loops called spin networks.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The evolution of a spin network over time is called a spin foam.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The characteristic length scale of a spin foam is the Planck length, approximately 1.616×10−35 m, and so lengths shorter than the Planck length are not physically meaningful in LQG.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Is there a preferred interpretation of quantum mechanics?
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] ", give rise to the reality we perceive?
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Since its inception, the many counter-intuitive aspects and results of quantum mechanics have provoked strong philosophical debates and many interpretations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The arguments centre on the probabilistic nature of quantum mechanics, the difficulties with wavefunction collapse and the related measurement problem, and quantum nonlocality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Perhaps the only consensus that exists about these issues is that there is no consensus.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The views of Niels Bohr, Werner Heisenberg and other physicists are often grouped together as the "Copenhagen interpretation".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] According to these views, the probabilistic nature of quantum mechanics is not a *temporary* feature which will eventually be replaced by a deterministic theory, but is instead a *final* renunciation of the classical idea of "causality".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Bohr in particular emphasized that any well-defined application of the quantum mechanical formalism must always make reference to the experimental arrangement, due to the complementary nature of evidence obtained under different experimental situations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Copenhagen-type interpretations were adopted by Nobel laureates in quantum physics, including Bohr, Heisenberg, Schrödinger, Feynman, and Zeilinger as well as 21st-century researchers in quantum foundations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Albert Einstein, himself one of the founders of quantum theory, was troubled by its apparent failure to respect some cherished metaphysical principles, such as determinism and locality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Einstein's long-running exchanges with Bohr about the meaning and status of quantum mechanics are now known as the Bohr–Einstein debates.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Einstein believed that underlying quantum mechanics must be a theory that explicitly forbids action at a distance.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] He argued that quantum mechanics was incomplete, a theory that was valid but not fundamental, analogous to how thermodynamics is valid, but the fundamental theory behind it is statistical mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In 1935, Einstein and his collaborators Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen published an argument that the principle of locality implies the incompleteness of quantum mechanics, a thought experiment later termed the Einstein–Podolsky–Rosen paradox.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In 1964, John Bell showed that EPR's principle of locality, together with determinism, was actually incompatible with quantum mechanics: they implied constraints on the correlations produced by distance systems, now known as Bell inequalities, that can be violated by entangled particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Since then several experiments have been performed to obtain these correlations, with the result that they do in fact violate Bell inequalities, and thus falsify the conjunction of locality with determinism.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Bohmian mechanics shows that it is possible to reformulate quantum mechanics to make it deterministic, at the price of making it explicitly nonlocal.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] It attributes not only a wave function to a physical system but also a real position, which evolves deterministically under a nonlocal guiding equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The evolution of a physical system is given at all times by the Schrödinger equation together with the guiding equation; there is never a collapse of the wave function.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Everett's many-worlds interpretation, formulated in 1956, holds that *all* the possibilities described by quantum theory *simultaneously* occur in a multiverse composed of mostly independent parallel universes.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This is a consequence of removing the axiom of the collapse of the wave packet.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] All possible states of the measured system and the measuring apparatus, together with the observer, are present in a real physical quantum superposition.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] While the multiverse is deterministic, we perceive non-deterministic behavior governed by probabilities because we do not observe the multiverse as a whole but only one parallel universe at a time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Exactly how this is supposed to work has been the subject of much debate.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Several attempts have been made to make sense of this and derive the Born rule, with no consensus on whether they have been successful.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Relational quantum mechanics appeared in the late 1990s as a modern derivative of Copenhagen-type ideas, and QBism was developed some years later.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Quantum mechanics was developed in the early decades of the 20th century, driven by the need to explain phenomena that, in some cases, had been observed in earlier times.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Scientific inquiry into the wave nature of light began in the 17th and 18th centuries, when scientists such as Robert Hooke, Christiaan Huygens and Leonhard Euler proposed a wave theory of light based on experimental observations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In 1803 English polymath Thomas Young described the famous double-slit experiment.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This experiment played a major role in the general acceptance of the wave theory of light.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] During the early 19th century, chemical research by John Dalton and Amedeo Avogadro lent weight to the atomic theory of matter, an idea that James Clerk Maxwell, Ludwig Boltzmann and others built upon to establish the kinetic theory of gases.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The successes of kinetic theory gave further credence to the idea that matter is composed of atoms, yet the theory also had shortcomings that would only be resolved by the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] While the early conception of atoms from Greek philosophy had been that they were indivisible units – the word "atom" deriving from the Greek for 'uncuttable' – the 19th century saw the formulation of hypotheses about subatomic structure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] One important discovery in that regard was Michael Faraday's 1838 observation of a glow caused by an electrical discharge inside a glass tube containing gas at low pressure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Julius Plücker, Johann Wilhelm Hittorf and Eugen Goldstein carried on and improved upon Faraday's work, leading to the identification of cathode rays, which J.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Thomson found to consist of subatomic particles that would be called electrons.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The black-body radiation problem was discovered by Gustav Kirchhoff in 1859.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In 1900, Max Planck proposed the hypothesis that energy is radiated and absorbed in discrete "quanta" (or energy packets), yielding a calculation that precisely matched the observed patterns of black-body radiation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The word *quantum* derives from the Latin, meaning "how great" or "how much".
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] According to Planck, quantities of energy could be thought of as divided into "elements" whose size (*E*) would be proportional to their frequency (*ν*): $E=h\nu \$ , where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Planck cautiously insisted that this was only an aspect of the processes of absorption and emission of radiation and was not the *physical reality* of the radiation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In fact, he considered his quantum hypothesis a mathematical trick to get the right answer rather than a sizable discovery.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] However, in 1905 Albert Einstein interpreted Planck's quantum hypothesis realistically and used it to explain the photoelectric effect, in which shining light on certain materials can eject electrons from the material.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Niels Bohr then developed Planck's ideas about radiation into a model of the hydrogen atom that successfully predicted the spectral lines of hydrogen.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Einstein further developed this idea to show that an electromagnetic wave such as light could also be described as a particle (later called the photon), with a discrete amount of energy that depends on its frequency.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In his paper "On the Quantum Theory of Radiation", Einstein expanded on the interaction between energy and matter to explain the absorption and emission of energy by atoms.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Although overshadowed at the time by his general theory of relativity, this paper articulated the mechanism underlying the stimulated emission of radiation, which became the basis of the laser.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] This phase is known as the old quantum theory.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Never complete or self-consistent, the old quantum theory was rather a set of heuristic corrections to classical mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] The theory is now understood as a semi-classical approximation to modern quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In the mid-1920s quantum mechanics was developed to become the standard formulation for atomic physics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] In 1923, the French physicist Louis de Broglie put forward his theory of matter waves by stating that particles can exhibit wave characteristics and vice versa.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Building on de Broglie's approach, modern quantum mechanics was born in 1925, when the German physicists Werner Heisenberg, Max Born, and Pascual Jordan developed matrix mechanics and the Austrian physicist Erwin Schrödinger invented wave mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Born introduced the probabilistic interpretation of Schrödinger's wave function in July 1926.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] Thus, the entire field of quantum physics emerged, leading to its wider acceptance at the Fifth Solvay Conference in 1927.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] By 1930, quantum mechanics had been further unified and formalized by David Hilbert, Paul Dirac and John von Neumann with greater emphasis on measurement, the statistical nature of our knowledge of reality, and philosophical speculation about the 'observer'.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] It has since permeated many disciplines, including quantum chemistry, quantum electronics, quantum optics, and quantum information science.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] It also provides a useful framework for many features of the modern periodic table of elements, and describes the behaviors of atoms during chemical bonding and the flow of electrons in computer semiconductors, and therefore plays a crucial role in many modern technologies.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-mechanics] While quantum mechanics was constructed to describe the world of the very small, it is also needed to explain some macroscopic phenomena such as superconductors and superfluids.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] An example is a qubit used in quantum information processing.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] where $|\Psi \rangle$ is the quantum state of the qubit, and $|0\rangle$ , $|1\rangle$ denote particular solutions to the Schrödinger equation in Dirac notation weighted by the two probability amplitudes $c_{0}$ and $c_{1}$ that both are complex numbers.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] Here $|0\rangle$ corresponds to the classical 0 bit, and $|1\rangle$ to the classical 1 bit.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] The probabilities of measuring the system in the $|0\rangle$ or $|1\rangle$ state are given by $|c_{0}|^{2}$ and $|c_{1}|^{2}$ respectively (see the Born rule).
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] Before the measurement occurs the qubit is in a superposition of both states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] The interference fringes in the double-slit experiment provide another example of the superposition principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] The theory of quantum mechanics postulates that a wave equation completely describes the state of a quantum system at all times.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] Furthermore, this differential equation is restricted to be linear and homogeneous.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] These conditions mean that for any two solutions of the wave equation, $\Psi _{1}$ and $\Psi _{2}$ , a linear combination of those solutions also solve the wave equation: $\Psi =c_{1}\Psi _{1}+c_{2}\Psi _{2}$ for arbitrary complex coefficients $c_{1}$ and $c_{2}$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] If the wave equation has more than two solutions, combinations of all such solutions are again valid solutions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] This transformation is itself a quantum superposition and every position wave function can be represented as a superposition of momentum wave functions and vice versa.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] These superpositions involve an infinite number of component waves.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] Other transformations express a quantum solution as a superposition of eigenvectors, each corresponding to a possible result of a measurement on the quantum system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] An eigenvector $\psi _{i}$ for a mathematical operator, ${\hat {A}}$ , has the equation ${\hat {A}}\psi _{i}=\lambda _{i}\psi _{i}$ where $\lambda _{i}$ is one possible measured quantum value for the observable A .
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] A superposition of these eigenvectors can represent any solution: $\Psi =\sum _{n}a_{i}\psi _{i}.$ The states like $\psi _{i}$ are called basis states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] Important mathematical operations on quantum system solutions can be performed using only the coefficients of the superposition, suppressing the details of the superposed functions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] This leads to quantum systems expressed in the Dirac bra-ket notation: $|v\rangle =d_{1}|1\rangle +d_{2}|2\rangle$ This approach is especially effective for systems like quantum spin with no classical coordinate analog.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] Such shorthand notation is very common in textbooks and papers on quantum mechanics, and superposition of basis states is a fundamental tool in quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] where $|n\rangle$ are the energy eigenstates of the Hamiltonian.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] where $\phi _{\alpha }(x)=\langle x|\alpha \rangle$ is the projection of the state into the $|x\rangle$ basis and is called the wave function of the particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] In both instances we notice that $|\alpha \rangle$ can be expanded as a superposition of an infinite number of basis states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] is a solution of the Schrödinger equation but is not generally an eigenstate because $E_{n}$ and $E_{n'}$ are not generally equal.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] We say that $|\Psi \rangle$ is made up of a superposition of energy eigenstates.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] Now consider the more concrete case of an electron that has either spin up or down.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] where $|{\uparrow }\rangle$ and $|{\downarrow }\rangle$ denote spin-up and spin-down states respectively.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] where the probability of finding the particle with either spin up or down is normalized to 1.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] where we have a general state $\Psi$ is the sum of the tensor products of the position space wave functions and spinors.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] Successful experiments involving superpositions of relatively large (by the standards of quantum physics) objects have been performed.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] In quantum computers, a qubit is the analog of the classical information bit, but rather than having one of two distinct values, qubits are a superposition of two values.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] Controlling this superposition qubits is a central challenge in quantum computation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] The superposition needs to be robust to unintended interactions and yet interactions are needed for computing with qubits.
[src:quantum-mechanics/quantum-superposition] Qubit systems like nuclear spins with small coupling strength are robust to outside disturbances but the same small coupling makes it difficult to readout results.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The **Schrödinger equation** is a partial differential equation that governs the wave function of a non-relativistic quantum-mechanical system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Its discovery was a significant landmark in the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] It is named after Erwin Schrödinger, an Austrian physicist, who postulated the equation in 1925 and published it in 1926, forming the basis for the work that resulted in his Nobel Prize in Physics in 1933.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Conceptually, the Schrödinger equation is the quantum counterpart of Newton's second law in classical mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Given a set of known initial conditions, Newton's second law makes a mathematical prediction as to what path a given physical system will take over time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation gives the evolution over time of the wave function, the quantum-mechanical characterization of an isolated physical system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The equation was postulated by Schrödinger based on a postulate of Louis de Broglie that all matter has an associated matter wave.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The equation predicted bound states of the atom in agreement with experimental observations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation is not the only way to study quantum mechanical systems and make predictions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Other formulations of quantum mechanics include matrix mechanics, introduced by Werner Heisenberg, and the path integral formulation, developed chiefly by Richard Feynman.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] When these approaches are compared, the use of the Schrödinger equation is sometimes called "wave mechanics".
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The equation given by Schrödinger is nonrelativistic because it contains a first derivative in time and a second derivative in space, and therefore space and time are not on equal footing.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Paul Dirac incorporated special relativity and quantum mechanics into a single formulation that simplifies to the Schrödinger equation in the non-relativistic limit.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This is the Dirac equation, which contains a single derivative in both space and time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Another partial differential equation, the Klein–Gordon equation, led to a problem with probability density even though it was a relativistic wave equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The probability density could be negative, which is physically unviable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This was fixed by Dirac by taking the so-called square root of the Klein–Gordon operator and in turn introducing Dirac matrices.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In a modern context, the Klein–Gordon equation describes spin-less particles, while the Dirac equation describes spin-1/2 particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Introductory courses on physics or chemistry typically introduce the Schrödinger equation in a way that can be appreciated knowing only the concepts and notations of basic calculus, particularly derivatives with respect to space and time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The parameter m is the mass of the particle, and $V(x,t)$ is the *potential energy function* that represents the environment in which the particle exists.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The constant i is the imaginary unit, and $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant, which has units of action (energy multiplied by time).
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This vector is postulated to be normalized under the Hilbert space's inner product, that is, in Dirac notation it obeys $\langle \psi |\psi \rangle =1$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Physical quantities of interest – position, momentum, energy, spin – are represented by observables, which are self-adjoint operators acting on the Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] A wave function can be an eigenvector of an observable, in which case it is called an eigenstate, and the associated eigenvalue corresponds to the value of the observable in that eigenstate.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] More generally, the eigenvalue is degenerate and the probability is given by $\langle \psi |P_{\lambda }|\psi \rangle$ , where $P_{\lambda }$ is the projector onto its associated eigenspace.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] A momentum eigenstate would be a perfectly monochromatic wave of infinite extent, which is not square-integrable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Likewise a position eigenstate would be a Dirac delta distribution, not square-integrable and technically not a function at all.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Consequently, neither can belong to the particle's Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Physicists sometimes regard these eigenstates, composed of elements outside the Hilbert space, as "generalized eigenvectors".
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] These are used for calculational convenience and do not represent physical states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The form of the Schrödinger equation depends on the physical situation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] where t is time, $\vert \Psi (t)\rangle$ is the state vector of the quantum system ( $\Psi$ being the Greek letter psi), and ${\hat {H}}$ is an observable, the Hamiltonian operator.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The term "Schrödinger equation" can refer to both the general equation, or the specific nonrelativistic version.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The general equation is indeed quite general, used throughout quantum mechanics, for everything from the Dirac equation to quantum field theory, by plugging in diverse expressions for the Hamiltonian.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The specific nonrelativistic version is an approximation that yields accurate results in many situations, but only to a certain extent (see relativistic quantum mechanics and relativistic quantum field theory).
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] To apply the Schrödinger equation, write down the Hamiltonian for the system, accounting for the kinetic and potential energies of the particles constituting the system, then insert it into the Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The resulting partial differential equation is solved for the wave function, which contains information about the system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In practice, the square of the absolute value of the wave function at each point is taken to define a probability density function.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The time-dependent Schrödinger equation described above predicts that wave functions can form standing waves, called stationary states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] These states are particularly important as their individual study later simplifies the task of solving the time-dependent Schrödinger equation for *any* state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This is only used when the Hamiltonian itself is not dependent on time explicitly.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] However, even in this case the total wave function is dependent on time as explained in the section on linearity below.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In the language of linear algebra, this equation is an eigenvalue equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Therefore, the wave function is an eigenfunction of the Hamiltonian operator with corresponding eigenvalue(s) E .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Moreover, the sum can be extended for any number of state vectors.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This property allows superpositions of quantum states to be solutions of the Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Even more generally, it holds that a general solution to the Schrödinger equation can be found by taking a weighted sum over a basis of states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] A choice often employed is the basis of energy eigenstates, which are solutions of the time-independent Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Unitarity is a general feature of time evolution under the Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] If the initial state is $|\Psi (0)\rangle$ , then the state at a later time t will be given by $|\Psi (t)\rangle ={\hat {U}}(t)|\Psi (0)\rangle$ for some unitary operator ${\hat {U}}(t)$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Conversely, suppose that ${\hat {U}}(t)$ is a continuous family of unitary operators parameterized by t .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Without loss of generality, the parameterization can be chosen so that ${\hat {U}}(0)$ is the identity operator and that ${\hat {U}}(t/N)^{N}={\hat {U}}(t)$ for any $N>0$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Then ${\hat {U}}(t)$ depends upon the parameter t in such a way that ${\hat {U}}(t)=e^{-i{\hat {G}}t}$ for some self-adjoint operator ${\hat {G}}$ , called the *generator* of the family ${\hat {U}}(t)$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] A Hamiltonian is just such a generator (up to the factor of the Planck constant that would be set to 1 in natural units).
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation is often presented using quantities varying as functions of position, but as a vector-operator equation it has a valid representation in any arbitrary complete basis of kets in Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] As mentioned above, "bases" that lie outside the physical Hilbert space are also employed for calculational purposes.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This is illustrated by the *position-space* and *momentum-space* Schrödinger equations for a nonrelativistic, spinless particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] When restricted from three dimensions to one, the position-space equation is just the first form of the Schrödinger equation given above.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The relation between position and momentum in quantum mechanics can be appreciated in a single dimension.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Thus, ${\hat {p}}^{2}$ becomes a second derivative, and in three dimensions, the second derivative becomes the Laplacian $\nabla ^{2}$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The canonical commutation relation also implies that the position and momentum operators are Fourier conjugates of each other.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Consequently, functions originally defined in terms of their position dependence can be converted to functions of momentum using the Fourier transform.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In solid-state physics, the Schrödinger equation is often written for functions of momentum, as Bloch's theorem ensures the periodic crystal lattice potential couples ${\tilde {\Psi }}(p)$ with ${\tilde {\Psi }}(p+\hbar K)$ for only discrete reciprocal lattice vectors K .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This makes it convenient to solve the momentum-space Schrödinger equation at each point in the Brillouin zone independently of the other points in the Brillouin zone.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation is consistent with local probability conservation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] It also ensures that a normalized wavefunction remains normalized after time evolution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In matrix mechanics, this means that the time evolution operator is a unitary operator.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In contrast to, for example, the Klein Gordon equation, although a redefined inner product of a wavefunction can be time independent, the total volume integral of modulus square of the wavefunction need not be time independent.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Although the factor ${\textstyle {\nabla S}/{m}}$ appears to play the role of velocity, it does not represent velocity at a point since simultaneous measurement of position and velocity violates uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The spatial part of the full wave function solves the equation $\nabla ^{2}\psi (\mathbf {r} )+{\frac {2m}{\hbar ^{2}}}\left[E-V(\mathbf {r} )\right]\psi (\mathbf {r} )=0,$ where the energy E appears in the phase factor.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This generalizes to any number of particles in any number of dimensions (in a time-independent potential): the standing wave solutions of the time-independent equation are the states with definite energy, instead of a probability distribution of different energies.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In physics, these standing waves are called "stationary states" or "energy eigenstates"; in chemistry they are called "atomic orbitals" or "molecular orbitals".
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Superpositions of energy eigenstates change their properties according to the relative phases between the energy levels.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The energy eigenstates form a basis: any wave function may be written as a sum over the discrete energy states or an integral over continuous energy states, or more generally as an integral over a measure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This is an example of the spectral theorem, and in a finite-dimensional state space it is just a statement of the completeness of the eigenvectors of a Hermitian matrix.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Separation of variables can also be a useful method for the time-independent Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The box is defined as having zero potential energy *inside* a certain region and infinite potential energy *outside*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Furthermore, it can be used to describe approximately a wide variety of other systems, including vibrating atoms, molecules, and atoms or ions in lattices, and approximating other potentials near equilibrium points.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] It is also the basis of perturbation methods in quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The case $n=0$ is called the ground state, its energy is called the zero-point energy, and the wave function is a Gaussian.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The harmonic oscillator, like the particle in a box, illustrates the generic feature of the Schrödinger equation that the energies of bound eigenstates are discretized.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The negative sign arises in the potential term since the proton and electron are oppositely charged.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The reduced mass in place of the electron mass is used since the electron and proton together orbit each other about a common center of mass, and constitute a two-body problem to solve.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The motion of the electron is of principal interest here, so the equivalent one-body problem is the motion of the electron using the reduced mass.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation for a hydrogen atom can be solved by separation of variables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In this case, spherical polar coordinates are the most convenient.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Thus, $\psi (r,\theta ,\varphi )=R(r)\ Y_{\ell }^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )=R(r)\ \Theta (\theta )\ \Phi (\varphi ),$ where *R* are radial functions and $Y_{l}^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ are spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ and order m .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This is the only atom for which the Schrödinger equation has been solved exactly.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Multi-electron atoms require approximate methods.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] It is typically not possible to solve the Schrödinger equation exactly for situations of physical interest.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Accordingly, approximate solutions are obtained using techniques like variational methods and WKB approximation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] It is also common to treat a problem of interest as a small modification to a problem that can be solved exactly, a method known as perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] One simple way to compare classical to quantum mechanics is to consider the time-evolution of the *expected* position and *expected* momentum, which can then be compared to the time-evolution of the ordinary position and momentum in classical mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The quantum expectation values satisfy the Ehrenfest theorem.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] For a general $V'$ , therefore, quantum mechanics can lead to predictions where expectation values do not mimic the classical behavior.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In the case of the quantum harmonic oscillator, however, $V'$ is linear and this distinction disappears, so that in this very special case, the expected position and expected momentum do exactly follow the classical trajectories.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] For general systems, the best we can hope for is that the expected position and momentum will *approximately* follow the classical trajectories.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] If the wave function is highly concentrated around a point $x_{0}$ , then $V'\left(\left\langle X\right\rangle \right)$ and $\left\langle V'(X)\right\rangle$ will be *almost* the same, since both will be approximately equal to $V'(x_{0})$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In that case, the expected position and expected momentum will remain very close to the classical trajectories, at least for as long as the wave function remains highly localized in position.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Here the generalized coordinates $q_{i}$ for $i=1,2,3$ (used in the context of the HJE) can be set to the position in Cartesian coordinates as $\mathbf {r} =(q_{1},q_{2},q_{3})=(x,y,z)$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Substituting $\Psi ={\sqrt {\rho (\mathbf {r} ,t)}}e^{iS(\mathbf {r} ,t)/\hbar }$ where $\rho$ is the probability density, into the Schrödinger equation and then taking the limit $\hbar \to 0$ in the resulting equation yield the Hamilton–Jacobi equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Wave functions are not always the most convenient way to describe quantum systems and their behavior.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] When the preparation of a system is only imperfectly known, or when the system under investigation is a part of a larger whole, density matrices may be used instead.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] A density matrix is a positive semi-definite operator whose trace is equal to 1.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] (The term "density operator" is also used, particularly when the underlying Hilbert space is infinite-dimensional.) The set of all density matrices is convex, and the extreme points are the operators that project onto vectors in the Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The density-matrix analogue of the Schrödinger equation for wave functions is $i\hbar {\frac {\partial {\hat {\rho }}}{\partial t}}=[{\hat {H}},{\hat {\rho }}],$ where the brackets denote a commutator.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This is variously known as the von Neumann equation, the Liouville–von Neumann equation, or just the Schrödinger equation for density matrices.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Unitary evolution of a density matrix conserves its von Neumann entropy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The one-particle Schrödinger equation described above is valid only in the nonrelativistic domain.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The effect of a Galilean transformation upon the Schrödinger equation can be creates a phase factor times the wave function, but the probabilities, as calculated via the Born rule, are unchanged.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] But the time coordinate in the Schrödinger equation is not proper time and relativistic effects on mass are absent.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Moreover, processes that change particle number are natural in relativity, and so an equation for one particle (or any fixed number thereof) can only be of limited use.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] A more general form of the Schrödinger equation that also applies in relativistic situations can be formulated within quantum field theory (QFT), a framework that allows the combination of quantum mechanics with special relativity.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The region in which both simultaneously apply may be described by relativistic quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Such descriptions may use time evolution generated by a Hamiltonian operator, as in the Schrödinger functional method.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Attempts to combine quantum physics with special relativity began with building relativistic wave equations from the relativistic energy–momentum relation $E^{2}=(pc)^{2}+\left(m_{0}c^{2}\right)^{2},$ instead of nonrelativistic energy equations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Klein–Gordon equation and the Dirac equation are two such equations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Historically, Dirac obtained the Dirac equation by seeking a differential equation that would be first-order in both time and space, a desirable property for a relativistic theory.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Taking the "square root" of the left-hand side of the Klein–Gordon equation in this way required factorizing it into a product of two operators, which Dirac wrote using 4 × 4 matrices $\alpha _{1},\alpha _{2},\alpha _{3},\beta$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This has again the form of the Schrödinger equation, with the time derivative of the wave function being given by a Hamiltonian operator acting upon the wave function.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Including influences upon the particle requires modifying the Hamiltonian operator.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Dirac equation is true for all spin-1⁄2 particles, and the solutions to the equation are 4-component spinor fields with two components corresponding to the particle and the other two for the antiparticle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] For the Klein–Gordon equation, the general form of the Schrödinger equation is inconvenient to use, and in practice the Hamiltonian is not expressed in an analogous way to the Dirac Hamiltonian.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In general, the Hamiltonian to be substituted in the general Schrödinger equation is not just a function of the position and momentum operators (and possibly time), but also of spin matrices.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Also, the solutions to a relativistic wave equation, for a massive particle of spin *s*, are complex-valued 2(2*s* + 1)-component spinor fields.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] As originally formulated, the Dirac equation is an equation for a single quantum particle, just like the single-particle Schrödinger equation with wave function $\Psi (x,t)$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This is of limited use in relativistic quantum mechanics, where particle number is not fixed.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Heuristically, this complication can be motivated by noting that mass–energy equivalence implies material particles can be created from energy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] A common way to address this in QFT is to introduce a Hilbert space where the basis states are labeled by particle number, a so-called Fock space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation can then be formulated for quantum states on this Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] However, because the Schrödinger equation picks out a preferred time axis, the Lorentz invariance of the theory is no longer manifest, and accordingly, the theory is often formulated in other ways.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Following Max Planck's quantization of light (see black-body radiation), Albert Einstein interpreted Planck's quanta to be photons, particles of light, and proposed that the energy of a photon is proportional to its frequency, one of the first signs of wave–particle duality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Louis de Broglie hypothesized that this is true for all particles, even particles which have mass such as electrons.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] He showed that, assuming that the matter waves propagate along with their particle counterparts, electrons form standing waves, meaning that only certain discrete rotational frequencies about the nucleus of an atom are allowed.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] These quantized orbits correspond to discrete energy levels, and de Broglie reproduced the Bohr model formula for the energy levels.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This approach essentially confined the electron wave in one dimension, along a circular orbit of radius r .
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Lunn at the University of Chicago had used the same argument based on the completion of the relativistic energy–momentum 4-vector to derive what we now call the de Broglie relation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Following up on de Broglie's ideas, physicist Peter Debye made an offhand comment that if particles behaved as waves, they should satisfy some sort of wave equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Inspired by Debye's remark, Schrödinger decided to find a proper 3-dimensional wave equation for the electron.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] By that time Arnold Sommerfeld had refined the Bohr model with relativistic corrections.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] He found the standing waves of this relativistic equation, but the relativistic corrections disagreed with Sommerfeld's formula.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Discouraged, he put away his calculations and secluded himself with a mistress in a mountain cabin in December 1925.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] While at the cabin, Schrödinger decided that his earlier nonrelativistic calculations were novel enough to publish and decided to leave off the problem of relativistic corrections for the future.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Despite the difficulties in solving the differential equation for hydrogen (he had sought help from his friend the mathematician Hermann Weyl) Schrödinger showed that his nonrelativistic version of the wave equation produced the correct spectral energies of hydrogen in a paper published in 1926.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Schrödinger computed the hydrogen spectral series by treating a hydrogen atom's electron as a wave $\Psi (\mathbf {x} ,t)$ , moving in a potential well V , created by the proton.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This computation accurately reproduced the energy levels of the Bohr model.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation details the behavior of $\Psi$ but says nothing of its *nature*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Schrödinger tried to interpret the real part of $\Psi {\frac {\partial \Psi ^{*}}{\partial t}}$ as a charge density, and then revised this proposal, saying in his next paper that the modulus squared of $\Psi$ is a charge density.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This approach was, however, unsuccessful.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In 1926, just a few days after this paper was published, Max Born successfully interpreted $\Psi$ as the probability amplitude, whose modulus squared is equal to probability density.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation provides a way to calculate the wave function of a system and how it changes dynamically in time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] However, the Schrödinger equation does not directly say *what,* exactly, the wave function is.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The meaning of the Schrödinger equation and how the mathematical entities in it relate to physical reality depends upon the interpretation of quantum mechanics that one adopts.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] In the views often grouped together as the Copenhagen interpretation, a system's wave function is a collection of statistical information about that system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation relates information about the system at one time to information about it at another.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The wave function changes, according to this school of thought, because new information is available.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The post-measurement wave function generally cannot be known prior to the measurement, but the probabilities for the different possibilities can be calculated using the Born rule.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Other, more recent interpretations of quantum mechanics, such as relational quantum mechanics and QBism, view the Schrödinger equation in a similar way.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Schrödinger himself suggested in 1952 that the different terms of a superposition evolving under the Schrödinger equation are "not alternatives but all really happen simultaneously".
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This has been interpreted as an early version of Everett's many-worlds interpretation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This interpretation, formulated independently in 1956, holds that *all* the possibilities described by quantum theory *simultaneously* occur in a multiverse composed of mostly independent parallel universes.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] This interpretation removes the axiom of wave function collapse, leaving only continuous evolution under the Schrödinger equation, and so all possible states of the measured system and the measuring apparatus, together with the observer, are present in a real physical quantum superposition.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] While the multiverse is deterministic, we perceive non-deterministic behavior governed by probabilities, because we do not observe the multiverse as a whole, but only one parallel universe at a time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Why should we assign probabilities at all to outcomes that are certain to occur in some worlds, and why should the probabilities be given by the Born rule?
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Several ways to answer these questions in the many-worlds framework have been proposed, but there is no consensus on whether they are successful.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] Bohmian mechanics reformulates quantum mechanics to make it deterministic, at the price of adding a force due to a "quantum potential".
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] It attributes to each physical system not only a wave function but in addition a real position that evolves deterministically under a nonlocal guiding equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/schrödinger-equation] The evolution of a physical system is given at all times by the Schrödinger equation together with the guiding equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The **uncertainty principle**, also known as **Heisenberg's indeterminacy principle**, is a fundamental concept in quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] It states that there is a limit to the precision with which certain pairs of physical properties, such as position and momentum, can be simultaneously known.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In other words, the more accurately one property is measured, the less accurately the other property can be known.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] More formally, the uncertainty principle is any of a variety of mathematical inequalities asserting a fundamental limit to the product of the accuracy of certain related pairs of measurements on a quantum system, such as position, *x*, and momentum, *p*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Such paired-variables are known as complementary variables or canonically conjugate variables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] where $\hbar ={\frac {h}{2\pi }}$ is the reduced Planck constant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The quintessentially quantum mechanical uncertainty principle comes in many forms other than position–momentum.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The energy–time relationship is widely used to relate quantum state lifetime to measured energy widths but its formal derivation is fraught with confusing issues about the nature of time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The basic principle has been extended in numerous directions; it must be considered in many kinds of fundamental physical measurements.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] It is vital to illustrate how the principle applies to relatively intelligible physical situations since it is indiscernible on the macroscopic scales that humans experience.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Two alternative frameworks for quantum physics offer different explanations for the uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The wave mechanics picture of the uncertainty principle is more visually intuitive, but the more abstract matrix mechanics picture formulates it in a way that generalizes more easily.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Mathematically, in wave mechanics, the uncertainty relation between position and momentum arises because the expressions of the wavefunction in the two corresponding orthonormal bases in Hilbert space are Fourier transforms of one another (i.e., position and momentum are conjugate variables).
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] A nonzero function and its Fourier transform cannot both be sharply localized at the same time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In quantum mechanics, the two key points are that the position of the particle takes the form of a matter wave, and momentum is its Fourier conjugate, assured by the de Broglie relation *p* = *ħk*, where k is the wavenumber.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In matrix mechanics, the mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics, any pair of non-commuting self-adjoint operators representing observables are subject to similar uncertainty limits.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] An eigenstate of an observable represents the state of the wavefunction for a certain measurement value (the eigenvalue).
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] For example, if a measurement of an observable A is performed, then the system is in a particular eigenstate Ψ of that observable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] However, the particular eigenstate of the observable A need not be an eigenstate of another observable B: If so, then it does not have a unique associated measurement for it, as the system is not in an eigenstate of that observable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The uncertainty principle can be visualized using the position- and momentum-space wavefunctions for one spinless particle with mass in one dimension.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The more localized the position-space wavefunction, the more likely the particle is to be found with the position coordinates in that region, and correspondingly the momentum-space wavefunction is less localized so the possible momentum components the particle could have are more widespread.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] These wavefunctions are Fourier transforms of each other: mathematically, the uncertainty principle expresses the relationship between conjugate variables in the transform.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] amplitude is blue, imaginary part is green.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] is spread out like a waveform, there is no definite position of the particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] reverses sign, so the amplitude begins to decrease again, and vice versa—the result is an alternating amplitude: a wave.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] According to the de Broglie hypothesis, every object in the universe is associated with a wave.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Thus every object, from an elementary particle to atoms, molecules and on up to planets and beyond are subject to the uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In the case of the single-mode plane wave, $|\psi (x)|^{2}$ is 1 if $X=x$ and 0 otherwise.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In other words, the particle position is extremely uncertain in the sense that it could be essentially anywhere along the wave packet.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] On the other hand, consider a wave function that is a sum of many waves, which we may write as $\psi (x)\propto \sum _{n}A_{n}e^{ip_{n}x/\hbar }~,$ where *A**n* represents the relative contribution of the mode *p**n* to the overall total.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The figures to the right show how with the addition of many plane waves, the wave packet can become more localized.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In mathematical terms, we say that $\varphi (p)$ is the *Fourier transform* of $\psi (x)$ and that x and p are conjugate variables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Adding together all of these plane waves comes at a cost, namely the momentum has become less precise, having become a mixture of waves of many different momenta.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] One way to quantify the precision of the position and momentum is the standard deviation σ.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Since $|\psi (x)|^{2}$ is a probability density function for position, we calculate its standard deviation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The precision of the position is improved, i.e. reduced *σ**x*, by using many plane waves, thereby weakening the precision of the momentum, i.e. increased *σ**p*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Another way of stating this is that *σ**x* and *σ**p* have an inverse relationship or are at least bounded from below.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] This is the uncertainty principle, the exact limit of which is the Kennard bound.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Without loss of generality, we will assume that the means vanish, which just amounts to a shift of the origin of our coordinates.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The function $f(x)=x\cdot \psi (x)$ can be interpreted as a vector in a function space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] We can define an inner product for a pair of functions *u*(*x*) and *v*(*x*) in this vector space: $\langle u\mid v\rangle =\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }u^{*}(x)\cdot v(x)\,dx,$ where the asterisk denotes the complex conjugate.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] We can repeat this for momentum by interpreting the function ${\tilde {g}}(p)=p\cdot \varphi (p)$ as a vector, but we can also take advantage of the fact that $\psi (x)$ and $\varphi (p)$ are Fourier transforms of each other.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The term ${\textstyle -i\hbar {\frac {d}{dx}}}$ is called the momentum operator in position space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] All that remains is to evaluate these inner products.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] with equality if and only if *p* and *x* are linearly dependent.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Note that the only *physics* involved in this proof was that $\psi (x)$ and $\varphi (p)$ are wave functions for position and momentum, which are Fourier transforms of each other.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] A similar result would hold for *any* pair of conjugate variables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In matrix mechanics, observables such as position and momentum are represented by self-adjoint operators.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] When considering pairs of observables, an important quantity is the *commutator*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The physical meaning of the non-commutativity can be understood by considering the effect of the commutator on position and momentum eigenstates.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Let $|\psi \rangle$ be a right eigenstate of position with a constant eigenvalue *x*0.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Suppose, for the sake of proof by contradiction, that $|\psi \rangle$ is also a right eigenstate of momentum, with constant eigenvalue *p*0.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] When a state is measured, it is projected onto an eigenstate in the basis of the relevant observable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] For example, if a particle's position is measured, then the state amounts to a position eigenstate.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] This means that the state is *not* a momentum eigenstate, however, but rather it can be represented as a sum of multiple momentum basis eigenstates.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In other words, the momentum must be less precise.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] As in the wave mechanics interpretation above, one sees a tradeoff between the respective precisions of the two, quantified by the uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Consider a one-dimensional quantum harmonic oscillator.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In particular, the above Kennard bound is saturated for the ground state *n*=0, for which the probability density is just the normal distribution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Position (blue) and momentum (red) probability densities for an initial Gaussian distribution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Note the tradeoff between the widths of the distributions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Through integration over the propagator, we can solve for the full time-dependent solution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Moreover, every squeezed coherent state also saturates the Kennard bound although the individual contributions of position and momentum need not be balanced in general.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Consider a particle in a one-dimensional box of length L .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Since $\langle p(t)\rangle =p_{0}$ and $\sigma _{p}(t)=\hbar /({\sqrt {2}}x_{0})$ , this can be interpreted as a particle moving along with constant momentum at arbitrarily high precision.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The derivation shown here incorporates and builds off of those shown in Robertson, Schrödinger and standard textbooks such as Griffiths.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Since $\langle f\mid g\rangle$ is in general a complex number, we use the fact that the modulus squared of any complex number z is defined as $|z|^{2}=zz^{*}$ , where $z^{*}$ is the complex conjugate of z .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] We now substitute the above two equations above back into Eq.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] This proof has an issue related to the domains of the operators involved.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] For the proof to make sense, the vector ${\hat {B}}|\Psi \rangle$ has to be in the domain of the unbounded operator ${\hat {A}}$ , which is not always the case.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In fact, the Robertson uncertainty relation is false if ${\hat {A}}$ is an angle variable and ${\hat {B}}$ is the derivative with respect to this variable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In this example, the commutator is a nonzero constant—just as in the Heisenberg uncertainty relation—and yet there are states where the product of the uncertainties is zero.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] (See the counterexample section below.) This issue can be overcome by using a variational method for the proof, or by working with an exponentiated version of the canonical commutation relations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Note that in the general form of the Robertson–Schrödinger uncertainty relation, there is no need to assume that the operators ${\hat {A}}$ and ${\hat {B}}$ are self-adjoint operators.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] It suffices to assume that they are merely symmetric operators.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] (The distinction between these two notions is generally glossed over in the physics literature, where the term *Hermitian* is used for either or both classes of operators.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In the phase space formulation of quantum mechanics, the Robertson–Schrödinger relation follows from a positivity condition on a real star-square function.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Since this positivity condition is true for *all* *a*, *b*, and *c*, it follows that all the eigenvalues of the matrix are non-negative.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Since the Robertson and Schrödinger relations are for general operators, the relations can be applied to any two observables to obtain specific uncertainty relations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] A few of the most common relations found in the literature are given below.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The derivation of the Robertson inequality for operators ${\hat {A}}$ and ${\hat {B}}$ requires ${\hat {A}}{\hat {B}}\psi$ and ${\hat {B}}{\hat {A}}\psi$ to be defined.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] There are quantum systems where these conditions are not valid.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] One example is a quantum particle on a ring, where the wave function depends on an angular variable $\theta$ in the interval $[0,2\pi ]$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The definition of ${\hat {A}}$ depends the $\theta$ range from 0 to $2\pi$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] These operators satisfy the usual commutation relations for position and momentum operators, $[{\hat {A}},{\hat {B}}]=i\hbar$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] More precisely, ${\hat {A}}{\hat {B}}\psi -{\hat {B}}{\hat {A}}\psi =i\hbar \psi$ whenever both ${\hat {A}}{\hat {B}}\psi$ and ${\hat {B}}{\hat {A}}\psi$ are defined, and the space of such $\psi$ is a dense subspace of the quantum Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Now let $\psi$ be any of the eigenstates of ${\hat {B}}$ , which are given by $\psi (\theta )=e^{2\pi in\theta }$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] These states are normalizable, unlike the eigenstates of the momentum operator on the line.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Also the operator ${\hat {A}}$ is bounded, since $\theta$ ranges over a bounded interval.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] For the usual position and momentum operators ${\hat {X}}$ and ${\hat {P}}$ on the real line, no such counterexamples can occur.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] As long as $\sigma _{x}$ and $\sigma _{p}$ are defined in the state $\psi$ , the Heisenberg uncertainty principle holds, even if $\psi$ fails to be in the domain of ${\hat {X}}{\hat {P}}$ or of ${\hat {P}}{\hat {X}}$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The Robertson–Schrödinger uncertainty can be improved noting that it must hold for all components $\varrho _{k}$ in any decomposition of the density matrix given as $\varrho =\sum _{k}p_{k}\varrho _{k}.$ Here, for the probabilities $p_{k}\geq 0$ and $\sum _{k}p_{k}=1$ hold.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Thus, we need to calculate the bound of the Robertson–Schrödinger uncertainty for the mixed components of the quantum state rather than for the quantum state, and compute an average of their square roots.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The following expression is stronger than the Robertson–Schrödinger uncertainty relation $\sigma _{A}^{2}\sigma _{B}^{2}\geq \left[\max _{p_{k},\varrho _{k}}\sum _{k}p_{k}L(\varrho _{k})\right]^{2},$ where on the right-hand side there is a concave roof over the decompositions of the density matrix.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The improved relation above is saturated by all single-qubit quantum states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The Robertson–Schrödinger uncertainty relation can be trivial if the state of the system is chosen to be eigenstate of one of the observable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The stronger uncertainty relations proved by Lorenzo Maccone and Arun K.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Pati give non-trivial bounds on the sum of the variances for two incompatible observables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The form of $|{\bar {\Psi }}_{A+B}\rangle$ implies that the right-hand side of the new uncertainty relation is nonzero unless $|\Psi \rangle$ is an eigenstate of $(A+B)$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] One may note that $|\Psi \rangle$ can be an eigenstate of $(A+B)$ without being an eigenstate of either A or B .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] However, when $|\Psi \rangle$ is an eigenstate of one of the two observables the Heisenberg–Schrödinger uncertainty relation becomes trivial.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] But the lower bound in the new relation is nonzero unless $|\Psi \rangle$ is an eigenstate of both.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] An energy–time uncertainty relation like $\Delta E\Delta t\gtrsim \hbar /2,$ has a long, controversial history; the meaning of $\Delta t$ and $\Delta E$ varies and different formulations have different arenas of validity.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] An informal, heuristic meaning of the principle is the following: A state that only exists for a short time cannot have a definite energy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] To have a definite energy, the frequency of the state must be defined accurately, and this requires the state to hang around for many cycles, the reciprocal of the required accuracy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] For example, in spectroscopy, excited states have a finite lifetime.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] By the time–energy uncertainty principle, they do not have a definite energy, and, each time they decay, the energy they release is slightly different.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The average energy of the outgoing photon has a peak at the theoretical energy of the state, but the distribution has a finite width called the *natural linewidth*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Fast-decaying states have a broad linewidth, while slow-decaying states have a narrow linewidth.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The same linewidth effect also makes it difficult to specify the rest mass of unstable, fast-decaying particles in particle physics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The faster the particle decays (the shorter its lifetime), the less certain is its mass (the larger the particle's width).
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The concept of "time" in quantum mechanics offers many challenges.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] There is no quantum theory of time measurement; relativity is both fundamental to time and difficult to include in quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] While position and momentum are associated with a single particle, time is a system property: it has no operator needed for the Robertson–Schrödinger relation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The mathematical treatment of stable and unstable quantum systems differ.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] These factors combine to make energy–time uncertainty principles controversial.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Three notions of "time" can be distinguished: external, intrinsic, and observable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] External or laboratory time is seen by the experimenter; intrinsic time is inferred by changes in dynamic variables, like the hands of a clock or the motion of a free particle; observable time concerns time as an observable, the measurement of time-separated events.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] An external-time energy–time uncertainty principle might say that measuring the energy of a quantum system to an accuracy $\Delta E$ requires a time interval $\Delta t>h/\Delta E$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] However, Yakir Aharonov and David Bohm have shown that, in some quantum systems, energy can be measured accurately within an arbitrarily short time: external-time uncertainty principles are not universal.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Intrinsic time is the basis for several formulations of energy–time uncertainty relations, including the Mandelstam–Tamm relation discussed in the next section.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] A physical system with an intrinsic time closely matching the external laboratory time is called a "clock".
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Observable time, measuring time between two events, remains a challenge for quantum theories; some progress has been made using positive operator-valued measure concepts.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] In 1945, Leonid Mandelstam and Igor Tamm derived a non-relativistic *time–energy uncertainty relation* as follows.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] While this is a universal result, it depends upon the observable chosen and that the deviations $\sigma _{H}$ and $\sigma _{B}$ are computed for a particular state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] This $\tau _{B}$ can be interpreted as time for which the expectation value of the observable, $\langle {\hat {B}}\rangle ,$ changes by an amount equal to one standard deviation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Each example has a different meaning for the time uncertainty, according to the observable and state used.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Some formulations of quantum field theory uses temporary electron–positron pairs in its calculations called virtual particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The mass-energy and lifetime of these particles are related by the energy–time uncertainty relation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The energy of a quantum systems is not known with enough precision to limit their behavior to a single, simple history.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] Thus the influence of *all histories* must be incorporated into quantum calculations, including those with much greater or much less energy than the mean of the measured/calculated energy distribution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The energy–time uncertainty principle does not temporarily violate conservation of energy; it does not imply that energy can be "borrowed" from the universe as long as it is "returned" within a short amount of time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] The energy of the universe is not an exactly known parameter at all times.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p01] When events transpire at very short time intervals, there is uncertainty in the energy of these events.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In the context of harmonic analysis the uncertainty principle implies that one cannot at the same time localize the value of a function and its Fourier transform.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In the context of time–frequency analysis uncertainty principles are referred to as the **Gabor limit**, after Dennis Gabor, or sometimes the *Heisenberg–Gabor limit*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The basic result, which follows from "Benedicks's theorem", below, is that a function cannot be both time limited and band limited (a function and its Fourier transform cannot both have bounded domain)—see bandlimited versus timelimited.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] More accurately, the *time-bandwidth* or *duration-bandwidth* product satisfies $\sigma _{t}\sigma _{f}\geq {\frac {1}{4\pi }}\approx 0.08{\text{ cycles}},$ where $\sigma _{t}$ and $\sigma _{f}$ are the standard deviations of the time and frequency energy concentrations respectively.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Stated differently, one cannot simultaneously sharply localize a signal f in both the time domain and frequency domain.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Alternate theorems give more precise quantitative results, and, in time–frequency analysis, rather than interpreting the (1-dimensional) time and frequency domains separately, one instead interprets the limit as a lower limit on the support of a function in the (2-dimensional) time–frequency plane.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In practice, the Gabor limit limits the *simultaneous* time–frequency resolution one can achieve without interference; it is possible to achieve higher resolution, but at the cost of different components of the signal interfering with each other.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] As a result, in order to analyze signals where the transients are important, the wavelet transform is often used instead of the Fourier.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] This inequality is sharp, with equality achieved when *x* or *X* is a Dirac mass, or more generally when *x* is a nonzero multiple of a Dirac comb supported on a subgroup of the integers modulo *N* (in which case *X* is also a Dirac comb supported on a complementary subgroup, and vice versa).
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] More generally, if *T* and *W* are subsets of the integers modulo *N*, let $L_{T},R_{W}:\ell ^{2}(\mathbb {Z} /N\mathbb {Z} )\to \ell ^{2}(\mathbb {Z} /N\mathbb {Z} )$ denote the time-limiting operator and band-limiting operators, respectively.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Then $\|L_{T}R_{W}\|^{2}\leq {\frac {|T||W|}{|G|}}$ where the norm is the operator norm of operators on the Hilbert space $\ell ^{2}(\mathbb {Z} /N\mathbb {Z} )$ of functions on the integers modulo *N*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] This inequality has implications for signal reconstruction.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] When *N* is a prime number, a stronger inequality holds: $\|x\|_{0}+\|X\|_{0}\geq N+1.$ Discovered by Terence Tao, this inequality is also sharp.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Amrein–Berthier and Benedicks's theorem intuitively says that the set of points where f is non-zero and the set of points where ƒ̂ is non-zero cannot both be small.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Specifically, it is impossible for a function f in *L*2(**R**) and its Fourier transform ƒ̂ to both be supported on sets of finite Lebesgue measure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] One expects that the factor *Ce**C*|*S*||*Σ*| may be replaced by *Ce**C*(|*S*||*Σ*|)1/*d*, which is only known if either S or Σ is convex.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Hardy formulated the following uncertainty principle: it is not possible for f and ƒ̂ to both be "very rapidly decreasing".
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] This result was stated in Beurling's complete works without proof and proved in Hörmander (the case $d=1,N=0$ ) and Bonami, Demange, and Jaming for the general case.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Note that Hörmander–Beurling's version implies the case *ab* > 1 in Hardy's Theorem while the version by Bonami–Demange–Jaming covers the full strength of Hardy's Theorem.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] A different proof of Beurling's theorem based on Liouville's theorem appeared in ref.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] A full description of the case *ab* < 1 as well as the following extension to Schwartz class distributions appears in ref.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In quantum metrology, and especially interferometry, the **Heisenberg limit** is the optimal rate at which the accuracy of a measurement can scale with the energy used in the measurement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Typically, this is the measurement of a phase (applied to one arm of a beam-splitter) and the energy is given by the number of photons used in an interferometer.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Although some claim to have broken the Heisenberg limit, this reflects disagreement on the definition of the scaling resource.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Suitably defined, the Heisenberg limit is a consequence of the basic principles of quantum mechanics and cannot be beaten, although the weak Heisenberg limit can be beaten.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The inequalities above focus on the *statistical imprecision* of observables as quantified by the standard deviation $\sigma$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Heisenberg's original version, however, was dealing with the *systematic error*, a disturbance of the quantum system produced by the measuring apparatus, i.e., an observer effect.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Heisenberg's uncertainty principle, as originally described in the 1927 formulation, mentions only the first term of Ozawa inequality, regarding the *systematic error*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The formal derivation of the Heisenberg relation is possible but far from intuitive.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] It was *not* proposed by Heisenberg, but formulated in a mathematically consistent way only in recent years.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Also, it must be stressed that the Heisenberg formulation is not taking into account the intrinsic statistical errors $\sigma _{A}$ and $\sigma _{B}$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] There is increasing experimental evidence that the total quantum uncertainty cannot be described by the Heisenberg term alone, but requires the presence of all the three terms of the Ozawa inequality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The two simultaneous measurements on *A* and *B* are necessarily *unsharp* or *weak*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] It is also possible to derive an uncertainty relation that, as the Ozawa's one, combines both the statistical and systematic error components, but keeps a form very close to the Heisenberg original inequality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] For many distributions, the standard deviation is not a particularly natural way of quantifying the structure.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] For example, uncertainty relations in which one of the observables is an angle has little physical meaning for fluctuations larger than one period.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Other examples include highly bimodal distributions, or unimodal distributions with divergent variance.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] A solution that overcomes these issues is an uncertainty based on entropic uncertainty instead of the product of variances.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] While formulating the many-worlds interpretation of quantum mechanics in 1957, Hugh Everett III conjectured a stronger extension of the uncertainty principle based on entropic certainty.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] where the logarithms may be in any base.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Note that the entropies will be functions of these chosen parameters.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Depending on one's choice of the *x0 p0* product, the expression may be written in many ways.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] If *x*0 and *p*0 are chosen to be unity in whatever system of units are being used, then $H_{x}+H_{p}\geq \log \left({\frac {e\,h}{2}}\right)$ where h is interpreted as a dimensionless number equal to the value of the Planck constant in the chosen system of units.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Note that these inequalities can be extended to multimode quantum states, or wavefunctions in more than one spatial dimension.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The quantum entropic uncertainty principle is more restrictive than the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In other words, the Heisenberg uncertainty principle, is a consequence of the quantum entropic uncertainty principle, but not vice versa.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] First, the choice of base e is a matter of popular convention in physics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The logarithm can alternatively be in any base, provided that it be consistent on both sides of the inequality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Second, recall the Shannon entropy has been used, *not* the quantum von Neumann entropy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Finally, the normal distribution saturates the inequality, and it is the only distribution with this property, because it is the maximum entropy probability distribution among those with fixed variance (cf. here for proof).
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] A measurement apparatus will have a finite resolution set by the discretization of its possible outputs into bins, with the probability of lying within one of the bins given by the Born rule.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] We will consider the most common experimental situation, in which the bins are of uniform size.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Let *δx* be a measure of the spatial resolution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] We take the zeroth bin to be centered near the origin, with possibly some small constant offset *c*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Here we note that *δx* *δp*/*h* is a typical infinitesimal phase space volume used in the calculation of a partition function.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The inequality is also strict and not saturated.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Efforts to improve this bound are an active area of research.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] For a particle of total angular momentum j the following uncertainty relation holds $\sigma _{J_{x}}^{2}+\sigma _{J_{y}}^{2}+\sigma _{J_{z}}^{2}\geq j,$ where $J_{l}$ are angular momentum components.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In 1925 Heisenberg published the *Umdeutung* (reinterpretation) paper where he showed that central aspect of quantum theory was the non-commutativity: the theory implied that the relative order of position and momentum measurement was significant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Working with Max Born and Pascual Jordan, he continued to develop matrix mechanics, that would become the first modern quantum mechanics formulation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In March 1926, working in Bohr's institute, Heisenberg realized that the non-commutativity implies the uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Writing to Wolfgang Pauli in February 1927, he worked out the basic concepts.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Instead, he gave some plausible estimates in each case separately.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] His paper gave an analysis in terms of a microscope that Bohr showed was incorrect; Heisenberg included an addendum to the publication.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Any two variables that do not commute cannot be measured simultaneously—the more precisely one is known, the less precisely the other can be known.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] where *ħ* = ⁠*h*/2*π*⁠, and *σx*, *σp* are the standard deviations of position and momentum.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] (Heisenberg only proved relation (**A2**) for the special case of Gaussian states.) In 1929 Robertson generalized the inequality to all observables and in 1930 Schrödinger extended the form to allow non-zero covariance of the operators; this result is referred to as Robertson-Schrödinger inequality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Throughout the main body of his original 1927 paper, written in German, Heisenberg used the word "Ungenauigkeit", (Eng: Imprecision) to describe the basic theoretical principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Only in the endnote did he switch to the word "Unsicherheit" (Eng: Uncertainty).
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Later on, he always used "Unbestimmtheit" (Eng: Indefiniteness).
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] When the English-language version of Heisenberg's textbook, *The Physical Principles of the Quantum Theory*, was published in 1930, however, only the English word "uncertainty" was used, and it became the term in the English language.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The principle is quite counter-intuitive, so the early students of quantum theory had to be reassured that naive measurements to violate it were bound always to be unworkable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] One way in which Heisenberg originally illustrated the intrinsic impossibility of violating the uncertainty principle is by using the observer effect of an imaginary microscope as a measuring device.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] He imagines an experimenter trying to measure the position and momentum of an electron by shooting a photon at it.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The combination of these trade-offs implies that no matter what photon wavelength and aperture size are used, the product of the uncertainty in measured position and measured momentum is greater than or equal to a lower limit, which is (up to a small numerical factor) equal to the Planck constant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Heisenberg did not care to formulate the uncertainty principle as an exact limit, and preferred to use it instead, as a heuristic quantitative statement, correct up to small numerical factors, which makes the radically new noncommutativity of quantum mechanics inevitable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Historically, the uncertainty principle has been confused with a related effect in physics, called the observer effect, which notes that measurements of certain systems cannot be made without affecting the system, that is, without changing something in a system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Heisenberg used such an observer effect at the quantum level (see below) as a physical "explanation" of quantum uncertainty.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] It has since become clearer, however, that the uncertainty principle is inherent in the properties of all wave-like systems, and that it arises in quantum mechanics simply due to the matter wave nature of all quantum objects.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Thus, the uncertainty principle actually states a fundamental property of quantum systems and is not a statement about the observational success of current technology.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The Copenhagen interpretation of quantum mechanics and Heisenberg's uncertainty principle were, in fact, initially seen as twin targets by detractors.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] According to the Copenhagen interpretation of quantum mechanics, there is no fundamental reality that the quantum state describes, just a prescription for calculating experimental results.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] There is no way to say what the state of a system fundamentally is, only what the result of observations might be.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Albert Einstein believed that randomness is a reflection of our ignorance of some fundamental property of reality, while Niels Bohr believed that the probability distributions are fundamental and irreducible, and depend on which measurements we choose to perform.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Einstein and Bohr debated the uncertainty principle for many years.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Bohr's response was that the wall is quantum mechanical as well, and that to measure the recoil to accuracy Δ*p*, the momentum of the wall must be known to this accuracy before the particle passes through.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] This introduces an uncertainty in the position of the wall and therefore the position of the slit equal to ⁠*h*/Δ*p*⁠, and if the wall's momentum is known precisely enough to measure the recoil, the slit's position is uncertain enough to disallow a position measurement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] A similar analysis with particles diffracting through multiple slits is given by Richard Feynman.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Bohr was present when Einstein proposed the thought experiment which has become known as Einstein's box.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Einstein argued that "Heisenberg's uncertainty equation implied that the uncertainty in time was related to the uncertainty in energy, the product of the two being related to the Planck constant." Consider, he said, an ideal box, lined with mirrors so that it can contain light indefinitely.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The box could be weighed before a clockwork mechanism opened an ideal shutter at a chosen instant to allow one single photon to escape.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] "We now know, explained Einstein, precisely the time at which the photon left the box." "Now, weigh the box again.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] The change of mass tells the energy of the emitted light.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Bohr spent a sleepless night considering this argument, and eventually realized that it was flawed.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] He pointed out that if the box were to be weighed, say by a spring and a pointer on a scale, "since the box must move vertically with a change in its weight, there will be uncertainty in its vertical velocity and therefore an uncertainty in its height above the table. ...
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Furthermore, the uncertainty about the elevation above the Earth's surface will result in an uncertainty in the rate of the clock", because of Einstein's own theory of gravity's effect on time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In 1935, Einstein, Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen published an analysis of spatially separated entangled particles (EPR paradox).
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] According to EPR, one could measure the position of one of the entangled particles and the momentum of the second particle, and from those measurements deduce the position and momentum of both particles to any precision, violating the uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In order to avoid such possibility, the measurement of one particle must modify the probability distribution of the other particle instantaneously, possibly violating the principle of locality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In 1964, John Stewart Bell showed that this assumption can be falsified, since it would imply a certain inequality between the probabilities of different experiments.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Experimental results confirm the predictions of quantum mechanics, ruling out EPR's basic assumption of local hidden variables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Science philosopher Karl Popper approached the problem of indeterminacy as a logician and metaphysical realist.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] He disagreed with the application of the uncertainty relations to individual particles rather than to ensembles of identically prepared particles, referring to them as "statistical scatter relations".
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] In this statistical interpretation, a *particular* measurement may be made to arbitrary precision without invalidating the quantum theory.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Popper proposed an experiment to falsify the uncertainty relations, although he later withdrew his initial version after discussions with Carl Friedrich von Weizsäcker, Heisenberg, and Einstein; Popper sent his paper to Einstein and it may have influenced the formulation of the EPR paradox.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Some scientists, including Arthur Compton and Martin Heisenberg, have suggested that the uncertainty principle, or at least the general probabilistic nature of quantum mechanics, could be evidence for the two-stage model of free will.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] One critique, however, is that apart from the basic role of quantum mechanics as a foundation for chemistry, nontrivial biological mechanisms requiring quantum mechanics are unlikely, due to the rapid decoherence time of quantum systems at room temperature.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Proponents of this theory commonly say that this decoherence is overcome by both screening and decoherence-free subspaces found in biological cells.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] There is reason to believe that violating the uncertainty principle also strongly implies the violation of the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Uncertainty principles relate quantum particles – electrons for example – to classical concepts – position and momentum.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] This presumes quantum particles have position and momentum.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] From this point of view the uncertainty principle is not a fundamental quantum property but a concept "carried over from the language of our ancestors", as Kemble says.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Since the uncertainty principle is such a basic result in quantum mechanics, typical experiments in quantum mechanics routinely observe aspects of it.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] All forms of spectroscopy, including particle physics use the relationship to relate measured energy line-width to the lifetime of quantum states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Certain experiments, however, may deliberately test a particular form of the uncertainty principle as part of their main research program.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] These include, for example, tests of number–phase uncertainty relations in superconducting or quantum optics systems.
[src:quantum-mechanics/uncertainty-principle-p02] Applications dependent on the uncertainty principle for their operation include extremely low-noise technology such as that required in gravitational wave interferometers.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In quantum mechanics, a **wave function** (or **wavefunction**) is a mathematical description of the quantum state of an isolated quantum system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The most common symbols for a wave function are the Greek letters *ψ* and Ψ (lower-case and capital psi, respectively).
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] According to the superposition principle of quantum mechanics, wave functions can be added together and multiplied by complex numbers to form new wave functions and form a Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The inner product of two wave functions is a measure of the overlap between the corresponding physical states and is used in the foundational probabilistic interpretation of quantum mechanics, the Born rule, relating transition probabilities to inner products.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The Schrödinger equation determines how wave functions evolve over time, and a wave function behaves qualitatively like other waves, such as water waves or waves on a string, because the Schrödinger equation is mathematically a type of wave equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This explains the name "wave function", and gives rise to wave–particle duality.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] However, whether the wave function in quantum mechanics describes a kind of physical phenomenon is still open to different interpretations, fundamentally differentiating it from classic mechanical waves.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For example, a wave function might assign a complex number to each point in a region of space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The Born rule provides the means to turn these complex probability amplitudes into actual probabilities.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In one common form, it says that the squared modulus of a wave function that depends upon position is the probability density of measuring a particle as being at a given place.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The integral of a wavefunction's squared modulus over all the system's degrees of freedom must be equal to 1, a condition called *normalization*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Since the wave function is complex-valued, only its relative phase and relative magnitude can be measured; its value does not, in isolation, tell anything about the magnitudes or directions of measurable observables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] One has to apply quantum operators, whose eigenvalues correspond to sets of possible results of measurements, to the wave function *ψ* and calculate the statistical distributions for measurable quantities.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Wave functions can be functions of variables other than position, such as momentum.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The information represented by a wave function that is dependent upon position can be converted into a wave function dependent upon momentum and vice versa, by means of a Fourier transform.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Some particles, like electrons and photons, have nonzero spin, and the wave function for such particles includes spin as an intrinsic, discrete degree of freedom; other discrete variables can also be included, such as isospin.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] When a system has internal degrees of freedom, the wave function at each point in the continuous degrees of freedom (e.g., a point in space) assigns a complex number for *each* possible value of the discrete degrees of freedom (e.g., z-component of spin).
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] These values are often displayed in a column matrix (e.g., a 2 × 1 column vector for a non-relativistic electron with spin 1⁄2).
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In 1900, Max Planck postulated the proportionality between the frequency f of a photon and its energy E , $E=hf$ , and in 1916 the corresponding relation between a photon's momentum p and wavelength $\lambda$ , $\lambda ={\frac {h}{p}}$ , where h is the Planck constant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In 1923, De Broglie was the first to suggest that the relation $\lambda ={\frac {h}{p}}$ , now called the De Broglie relation, holds for *massive* particles, the chief clue being Lorentz invariance, and this can be viewed as the starting point for the modern development of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The equations represent wave–particle duality for both massless and massive particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In the 1920s and 1930s, quantum mechanics was developed using calculus and linear algebra.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Those who used the techniques of calculus included Louis de Broglie, Erwin Schrödinger, and others, developing "wave mechanics".
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Those who applied the methods of linear algebra included Werner Heisenberg, Max Born, and others, developing "matrix mechanics".
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Schrödinger subsequently showed that the two approaches were equivalent.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In 1926, Schrödinger published the famous wave equation now named after him, the Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This equation was based on classical conservation of energy using quantum operators and the de Broglie relations and the solutions of the equation are the wave functions for the quantum system.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] However, no one was clear on how to interpret it.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] At first, Schrödinger and others thought that wave functions represent particles that are spread out with most of the particle being where the wave function is large.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This was shown to be incompatible with the elastic scattering of a wave packet (representing a particle) off a target; it spreads out in all directions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] While a scattered particle may scatter in any direction, it does not break up and take off in all directions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In 1926, Born provided the perspective of probability amplitude.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This relates calculations of quantum mechanics directly to probabilistic experimental observations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] It is accepted as part of the Copenhagen interpretation of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] There are many other interpretations of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In 1927, Hartree and Fock made the first step in an attempt to solve the *N*-body wave function, and developed the *self-consistency cycle*: an iterative algorithm to approximate the solution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Now it is also known as the Hartree–Fock method.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The Slater determinant and permanent (of a matrix) was part of the method, provided by John C.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Schrödinger did encounter an equation for the wave function that satisfied relativistic energy conservation *before* he published the non-relativistic one, but discarded it as it predicted negative probabilities and negative energies.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In 1927, Klein, Gordon and Fock also found it, but incorporated the electromagnetic interaction and proved that it was Lorentz invariant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] De Broglie also arrived at the same equation in 1928.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This relativistic wave equation is now most commonly known as the Klein–Gordon equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In 1927, Pauli phenomenologically found a non-relativistic equation to describe spin-1/2 particles in electromagnetic fields, now called the Pauli equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Pauli found the wave function was not described by a single complex function of space and time, but needed two complex numbers, which respectively correspond to the spin +1/2 and −1/2 states of the fermion.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Soon after in 1928, Dirac found an equation from the first successful unification of special relativity and quantum mechanics applied to the electron, now called the Dirac equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In this, the wave function is a *spinor* represented by four complex-valued components: two for the electron and two for the electron's antiparticle, the positron.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In the non-relativistic limit, the Dirac wave function resembles the Pauli wave function for the electron.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Later, other relativistic wave equations were found.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] All these wave equations are of enduring importance.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The Schrödinger equation and the Pauli equation are under many circumstances excellent approximations of the relativistic variants.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] They are considerably easier to solve in practical problems than the relativistic counterparts.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The Klein–Gordon equation and the Dirac equation, while being relativistic, do not represent full reconciliation of quantum mechanics and special relativity.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The branch of quantum mechanics where these equations are studied the same way as the Schrödinger equation, often called relativistic quantum mechanics, while very successful, has its limitations (see e.g.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Lamb shift) and conceptual problems (see e.g.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Relativity makes it inevitable that the number of particles in a system is not constant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For full reconciliation, quantum field theory is needed.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In this theory, the wave equations and the wave functions have their place, but in a somewhat different guise.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The main objects of interest are not the wave functions, but rather operators, so called *field operators* (or just fields where "operator" is understood) on the Hilbert space of states (to be described next section).
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] It turns out that the original relativistic wave equations and their solutions are still needed to build the Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Moreover, the *free fields operators*, i.e. when interactions are assumed not to exist, turn out to (formally) satisfy the same equation as do the fields (wave functions) in many cases.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Thus the Klein–Gordon equation (spin 0) and the Dirac equation (spin 1⁄2) in this guise remain in the theory.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Higher spin analogues include the Proca equation (spin 1), Rarita–Schwinger equation (spin 3⁄2), and, more generally, the Bargmann–Wigner equations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For *massless* free fields two examples are the free field Maxwell equation (spin 1) and the free field Einstein equation (spin 2) for the field operators.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] All of them are essentially a direct consequence of the requirement of Lorentz invariance.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Their solutions must transform under Lorentz transformation in a prescribed way, i.e. under a particular representation of the Lorentz group and that together with few other reasonable demands, e.g. the cluster decomposition property, with implications for causality is enough to fix the equations.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This applies to free field equations; interactions are not included.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] If a Lagrangian density (including interactions) is available, then the Lagrangian formalism will yield an equation of motion at the classical level.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This equation may be very complex and not amenable to solution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Any solution would refer to a *fixed* number of particles and would not account for the term "interaction" as referred to in these theories, which involves the creation and annihilation of particles and not external potentials as in ordinary "first quantized" quantum theory.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In string theory, the situation remains analogous.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For instance, a wave function in momentum space has the role of Fourier expansion coefficient in a general state of a particle (string) with momentum that is not sharply defined.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Classical particles, like bullets, rockets and planets are spatially localized.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Classical waves like sound and ocean waves expand over large spatial regions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Quantum wave-particle duality is a unique characteristic of quantum particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For instance, spatially localized atoms are stable due to the existence of waves associate to the electrons in the atom.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] There is no consensus about the nature of the waves associated to quantum particles; however, there is consensus on how to calculate the mathematical expressions corresponding to these waves.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In non-relativistic quantum mechanics, there is a wave associate to a spin-0 quantum particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The Schrödinger wave equation should be solved for obtaining the mathematical expression corresponding to this "Schrödinger" wave.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] However, in relativistic quantum mechanics a relativistic wave equation should be solved.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Alternatively, a pair of relativistic but Schrödinger-like wave equations could be solved for obtaining the mathematical expressions of the two Schrödinger-like waves associated to a spin-0 relativistic quantum particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] There is no wave associated with a classical particle, but there is one Schrödinger wave associated with a spin-0 non-relativistic quantum particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Moreover, there are two Schrödinger waves associated with a spin-0 relativistic quantum particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Free classical and non-relativistic quantum particles have positive kinetic energies.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] However, a relativistic quantum particle could be associate with an "ordinary" Schrödinger-like wave where the particle has positive kinetic energy, but it could also be associated to an "extraordinary" Schrödinger wave where the particle has negative kinetic energy.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The existence of Schrödinger waves associated to a particle determines the quantum characteristics of the quantum particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] If for any reason the Schrödinger waves disappear, then the particle lost is quantum nature and it transforms in a classical particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Several transcendent instances of such quantum to classical transitions have been proposed for explaining why the macroscopic objects surrounding us seems to be classical and matter-only made of.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For now, consider the simple case of a non-relativistic single particle, without spin, in one spatial dimension.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] According to the postulates of quantum mechanics, the state of a physical system, at fixed time t , is given by the wave function belonging to a separable complex Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The number ‖Ψ‖ (not ‖Ψ‖2) is called the **norm** of the wave function Ψ.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The separable Hilbert space being considered is infinite-dimensional, which means there is no finite set of square integrable functions which can be added together in various combinations to create every possible square integrable function.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The state of such a particle is completely described by its wave function, $\Psi (x,t)\,,$ where x is position and t is time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This is a complex-valued function of two real variables x and t.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The asterisk indicates the complex conjugate.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] If the particle's position is measured, its location cannot be determined from the wave function, but is described by a probability distribution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The probability that its position *x* will be in the interval *a* ≤ *x* ≤ *b* is the integral of the density over this interval: $P_{a\leq x\leq b}(t)=\int _{a}^{b}\,|\Psi (x,t)|^{2}dx$ where t is the time at which the particle was measured.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This leads to the **normalization condition**: $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }\,|\Psi (x,t)|^{2}dx=1\,,$ because if the particle is measured, there is 100% probability that it will be *somewhere*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For a given system, the set of all possible normalizable wave functions (at any given time) forms an abstract mathematical vector space, meaning that it is possible to add together different wave functions, and multiply wave functions by complex numbers.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Technically, wave functions form a ray in a projective Hilbert space rather than an ordinary vector space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] At a particular instant of time, all values of the wave function Ψ(*x*, *t*) are components of a vector.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] There are uncountably infinitely many of them and integration is used in place of summation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In Bra–ket notation, this vector is written $|\Psi (t)\rangle =\int \Psi (x,t)|x\rangle dx$ and is referred to as a "quantum state vector", or simply "quantum state".
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The time parameter is often suppressed, and will be in the following.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Finding the identity operator in a basis allows the abstract state to be expressed explicitly in a basis, and more (the inner product between two state vectors, and other operators for observables, can be expressed in the basis).
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The particle also has a wave function in momentum space: $\Phi (p,t)$ where p is the momentum in one dimension, which can be any value from −∞ to +∞, and t is time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] One particular solution to the time-independent Schrödinger equation is $\Psi _{p}(x)=e^{ipx/\hbar },$ a plane wave, which can be used in the description of a particle with momentum exactly p, since it is an eigenfunction of the momentum operator.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] These functions are not normalizable to unity (they are not square-integrable), so they are not really elements of physical Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The set $\{\Psi _{p}(x,t),-\infty \leq p\leq \infty \}$ forms what is called the **momentum basis**.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This "basis" is not a basis in the usual mathematical sense.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For another thing, though they are linearly independent, there are too many of them (they form an uncountable set) for a basis for physical Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] They can still be used to express all functions in it using Fourier transforms as described next.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The position-space and momentum-space wave functions are thus found to be Fourier transforms of each other.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] They are two representations of the same state; containing the same information, and either one is sufficient to calculate any property of the particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In practice, the position-space wave function is used much more often than the momentum-space wave function.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The potential entering the relevant equation (Schrödinger, Dirac, etc.) determines in which basis the description is easiest.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For the harmonic oscillator, x and p enter symmetrically, so there it does not matter which description one uses.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The same equation (modulo constants) results.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] From this, with a little bit of afterthought, it follows that solutions to the wave equation of the harmonic oscillator are eigenfunctions of the Fourier transform in *L*2.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Following are the general forms of the wave function for systems in higher dimensions and more particles, as well as including other degrees of freedom than position coordinates or momentum components.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] While Hilbert spaces originally refer to infinite dimensional complete inner product spaces they, by definition, include finite dimensional complete inner product spaces as well.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In physics, they are often referred to as *finite dimensional Hilbert spaces*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For every finite dimensional Hilbert space there exist orthonormal basis kets that span the entire Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] $P=\sum _{i}|\phi _{i}\rangle \langle \phi _{i}|=I$ where the projection is equivalent to identity operator since ${\textstyle \{|\phi _{i}\rangle \}}$ spans the entire Hilbert space, thus leaving any vector from Hilbert space unchanged.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This is also known as completeness relation of finite dimensional Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] $|\psi \rangle =I|\psi \rangle =\sum _{i}|\phi _{i}\rangle \langle \phi _{i}|\psi \rangle$ where ${\textstyle \{\langle \phi _{i}|\psi \rangle \}}$ , is a set of complex numbers which can be used to construct a wavefunction using the above formula.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The equality follows due to orthogonal nature of ${\textstyle \{|\phi _{i}\rangle \}}$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Hence, ${\textstyle \{\langle \phi _{i}|\psi \rangle \}}$ which specify state of the quantum mechanical system, have magnitudes whose square gives the probability of measuring the respective ${\textstyle |\phi _{i}\rangle }$ state.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] While the relative phase has observable effects in experiments, the global phase of the system is experimentally indistinguishable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For example in a particle in superposition of two states, the global phase of the particle cannot be distinguished by finding expectation value of observable or probabilities of observing different states but relative phases can affect the expectation values of observables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] While the overall phase of the system is considered to be arbitrary, the relative phase for each state ${\textstyle |\phi _{i}\rangle }$ of a prepared state in superposition can be determined based on physical meaning of the prepared state and its symmetry.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For example, the construction of spin states along x direction as a superposition of spin states along z direction, can done by applying appropriate rotation transformation on the spin along z states which provides appropriate phase of the states relative to each other.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] An example of finite dimensional Hilbert space can be constructed using spin eigenkets of ${\textstyle s}$ -spin particles which forms a ${\textstyle 2s+1}$ dimensional Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] However, the general wavefunction of a particle that fully describes its state, is always from an infinite dimensional Hilbert space since it involves a tensor product with Hilbert space relating to the position or momentum of the particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Nonetheless, the techniques developed for finite dimensional Hilbert space are useful since they can either be treated independently or treated in consideration of linearity of tensor product.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] but it is a common abuse of notation, because the kets |*sz*⟩ are not synonymous or equal to the column vectors.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Column vectors simply provide a convenient way to express the spin components.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] since the eigenvectors of z-component spin operator are the above column vectors, with eigenvalues being the corresponding spin quantum numbers.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In the following discussion involving spin, the complete wavefunction is considered as tensor product of spin states from finite dimensional Hilbert spaces and the wavefunction which was previously developed.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The basis for this Hilbert space are hence considered: $|\mathbf {r} ,s_{z}\rangle =|\mathbf {r} \rangle |s_{z}\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The position-space wave function of a single particle without spin in three spatial dimensions is similar to the case of one spatial dimension above: $\Psi (\mathbf {r} ,t)$ where **r** is the position vector in three-dimensional space, and *t* is time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] As always Ψ(**r**, *t*) is a complex-valued function of real variables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] All the previous remarks on inner products, momentum space wave functions, Fourier transforms, and so on extend to higher dimensions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For a particle with spin, ignoring the position degrees of freedom, the wave function is a function of spin only (time is a parameter); $\xi (s_{z},t)$ where *s*z is the spin projection quantum number along the z axis.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] (The z axis is an arbitrary choice; other axes can be used instead if the wave function is transformed appropriately, see below.) The *sz* parameter, unlike **r** and t, is a discrete variable.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For example, for a spin-1/2 particle, *s*z can only be +1/2 or −1/2, and not any other value.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Inserting each quantum number gives a complex valued function of space and time, there are 2*s* + 1 of them.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The entire vector *ξ* is a solution of the Schrödinger equation (with a suitable Hamiltonian), which unfolds to a coupled system of 2*s* + 1 ordinary differential equations with solutions *ξ*(*s*, *t*), *ξ*(*s* − 1, *t*), ..., *ξ*(−*s*, *t*).
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The term "spin function" instead of "wave function" is used by some authors.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This contrasts the solutions to position space wave functions, the position coordinates being continuous degrees of freedom, because then the Schrödinger equation does take the form of a wave equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The tensor product factorization of energy eigenstates is always possible if the orbital and spin angular momenta of the particle are separable in the Hamiltonian operator underlying the system's dynamics (in other words, the Hamiltonian can be split into the sum of orbital and spin terms).
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The time dependence can be placed in either factor, and time evolution of each can be studied separately.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Under such Hamiltonians, any tensor product state evolves into another tensor product state, which essentially means any unentangled state remains unentangled under time evolution.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This is said to happen when there is no physical interaction between the states of the tensor products.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In the case of non separable Hamiltonians, energy eigenstates are said to be some linear combination of such states, which need not be factorizable; examples include a particle in a magnetic field, and spin–orbit coupling.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The preceding discussion is not limited to spin as a discrete variable, the total angular momentum *J* may also be used.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Other discrete degrees of freedom, like isospin, can expressed similarly to the case of spin above.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] If there are many particles, in general there is only one wave function, not a separate wave function for each particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The fact that *one* wave function describes *many* particles is what makes quantum entanglement and the EPR paradox possible.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The position-space wave function for *N* particles is written: $\Psi (\mathbf {r} _{1},\mathbf {r} _{2}\cdots \mathbf {r} _{N},t)$ where **r***i* is the position of the i-th particle in three-dimensional space, and t is time.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Altogether, this is a complex-valued function of 3*N* + 1 real variables.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In quantum mechanics there is a fundamental distinction between *identical particles* and *distinguishable* particles.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For example, any two electrons are identical and fundamentally indistinguishable from each other; the laws of physics make it impossible to "stamp an identification number" on a certain electron to keep track of it.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In other words, the wave function is either totally symmetric in the positions of bosons, or totally antisymmetric in the positions of fermions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The physical interchange of particles corresponds to mathematically switching arguments in the wave function.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The antisymmetry feature of fermionic wave functions leads to the Pauli principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Generally, bosonic and fermionic symmetry requirements are the manifestation of particle statistics and are present in other quantum state formalisms.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For *N* *distinguishable* particles (no two being identical, i.e. no two having the same set of quantum numbers), there is no requirement for the wave function to be either symmetric or antisymmetric.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For a collection of particles, some identical with coordinates **r**1, **r**2, ... and others distinguishable **x**1, **x**2, ...
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Again, there is no symmetry requirement for the distinguishable particle coordinates **x***i*.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For identical particles, symmetry requirements apply to both position and spin arguments of the wave function so it has the overall correct symmetry.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The formulae for the inner products are integrals over all coordinates or momenta and sums over all spin quantum numbers.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The differential volume elements *d*3**r***i* are also written "*dV**i*" or "*dxi dyi dzi*".
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The multidimensional Fourier transforms of the position or position–spin space wave functions yields momentum or momentum–spin space wave functions.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Hence the spacial variation of phase characterizes the probability flux.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In classical analogy, for ${\textstyle \mathbf {J} =\rho \mathbf {v} }$ , the quantity ${\textstyle {\frac {\nabla S}{m}}}$ is analogous with velocity.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Note that this does not imply a literal interpretation of ${\textstyle {\frac {\nabla S}{m}}}$ as velocity since velocity and position cannot be simultaneously determined as per the uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Which is analogous to Hamilton-Jacobi equation from classical mechanics.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] This interpretation fits with Hamilton–Jacobi theory, in which ${\textstyle \mathbf {P} _{\text{class.}}=\nabla S}$ , where *S* is Hamilton's principal function.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For systems in time-independent potentials, the wave function can always be written as a function of the degrees of freedom multiplied by a time-dependent phase factor, the form of which is given by the Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Wave functions of this form are called stationary states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The time dependence of the quantum state and the operators can be placed according to unitary transformations on the operators and states.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] For any quantum state |Ψ⟩ and operator *O*, in the Schrödinger picture |Ψ(*t*)⟩ changes with time according to the Schrödinger equation while *O* is constant.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In the Heisenberg picture it is the other way round, |Ψ⟩ is constant while *O*(*t*) evolves with time according to the Heisenberg equation of motion.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The Dirac (or interaction) picture is intermediate, time dependence is places in both operators and states which evolve according to equations of motion.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] It is useful primarily in computing S-matrix elements.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The following are solutions to the Schrödinger equation for one non-relativistic spinless particle.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] One of the most prominent features of wave mechanics is the possibility for a particle to reach a location with a prohibitive (in classical mechanics) force potential.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Note that these wave functions are not normalized; see scattering theory for discussion.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The standard interpretation of this is as a stream of particles being fired at the step from the left (the direction of negative x): setting *A*r = 1 corresponds to firing particles singly; the terms containing *A*r and *C*r signify motion to the right, while *A*l and *C*l – to the left.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Under this beam interpretation, put *C*l = 0 since no particles are coming from the right.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] By applying the continuity of wave functions and their derivatives at the boundaries, it is hence possible to determine the constants above.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] In a semiconductor crystallite whose radius is smaller than the size of its exciton Bohr radius, the excitons are squeezed, leading to quantum confinement.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The energy levels can then be modeled using the particle in a box model in which the energy of different states is dependent on the length of the box.
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] The wave functions of an electron in a Hydrogen atom are expressed in terms of spherical harmonics and generalized Laguerre polynomials (these are defined differently by different authors—see main article on them and the hydrogen atom).
[src:quantum-mechanics/wave-function-p01] Multi-electron atoms require approximative methods.
